<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A BIG trade in Asda stock options that led to a sharp rise in total volume
in the traded options was the outstanding feature in the derivatives, writes
Joel Kibazo.
The trade in Asda was said to have been carried out by NatWest Securities
and brought volume in the stock to a hefty 15,618 contracts. Total turnover
by the close was 46,052 lots, more than double Tuesday's 19,037 contracts.
British Aerospace, newly returned to the FT-SE 100 Index, was also a strong
feature and traded 2,920 contracts, to make it the second most active stock
option. That total was well above average for the derivative instrument and
reflected continued strength in the underlying equities. It was followed by
Hanson at 2,161 lots and British Steel at 1,318. Shell, Glaxo and BT were
also busy.
Hopes of a cut in interest rates brought an advance in the June futures
contract on the FT-SE 100, although volume remained thin. Having opened at
2,847, June traded lower in the first hour as independent traders sold
stock.
But the interest rates talk put paid to further selling and led to a strong
rise. It traded around the 2,860 level over the lunchtime period and
received a further boost by the firm opening on Wall Street, climbing to the
day's high of 2,875. June closed at 2,873, at a 7-point premium to the
underlying cash market. Turnover was 7,056 contracts.
</TEXT>
