<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: India tries to realise its food
export dream - Stefan Wagstyl reports on a switch to a more outward-looking
agricultural policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEFAN WAGSTYL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INDIAN GOVERNMENTS have long dreamt of turning the fertile fields of the
Punjab, in northern India, into an important source of export earnings.
The soil, water, and the weather are well-suited to the large-scale
production of cash crops and Punjabi farmers are among the most industrious
in India. The state is the largest contributor to the country's national
food stockpile.
And yet, Punjab's and India's food exports are minuscule. The country, the
world's second largest producer of fruit and vegetables and a leading grower
of grains, exports less than 1 per cent of its output.
The reformist government of Mr PV Narasimha Rao, the prime minister, now
wants to transform Indian agriculture. Earlier this year, it announced new
policies to promote agricultural exports with a view to increasing them from
USDollars 2.5bn in the year to March 1993 to Dollars 5bn-6bn in 1996-97. The
figure excludes tea and other traditional plantation crops such as coconuts,
but it includes fruit and vegetables, meat, grains, sugar and fish-farm
products.
Mr Pranab Mukherjee, the commerce minister, believes the policy changes will
stimulate rapid growth in agricultural exports because investments in
agriculture brought quick results. 'It will not take much time,' he says.
Punjabi businessmen think, however, that the government's target will be
hard to meet. They argue that it could be difficult to persuade farmers to
improve the quality of the crops to make them fit for export. Also, India
lacks the storage and transport facilities needed to deliver produce to
foreign markets. Mr Rohit Khanna, a consultant at Nijjer Agro Foods, one of
India's largest food processing companies, says the potential of Indian
agriculture is 'unbelievable' but it could take 20 years for it to be
fulfilled.
Moreover, businessmen say India cannot produce farm goods of international
quality without support from foreign food processing groups as only they can
provide the necessary seeds and technology. As Mr Khanna says: 'Without
prior experience it is impossible to develop a solid food processing
industry. Otherwise large Indian industrial groups would have moved into
agriculture long ago.'
The government's main concession is to permit businessmen to import
machinery and raw materials such as seeds duty-free for use in
export-oriented farms or food processing plants. Given that Indian import
duties are among the world's highest, this will greatly reduce the cost of
investing in modern equipment. Moreover, export-oriented units will be
obliged to export only 50 per cent of their output, leaving the rest for
sale in the Indian market.
At the same time, the government is easing a host of controls regulating the
flow of food supplies in India - including export restrictions on sugar,
grains, oils and other crops.
The controversial reforms represent a significant departure from
post-independence agricultural policy, a central plank of which has been
restraint of exports to keep down domestic food prices and reduce the risk
of famine. Mr Mukherjee says the new export-oriented policy will not hurt
domestic consumers because total output is rising and will increase further
with the new techniques that export-oriented producers will introduce.
However, many businessmen doubt whether the country's agricultural sector
can bring results as fast as the government expects.
They point to shortages of adequate cold storage warehouses, food processing
plants and refrigerated lorries. India processes less than 1.5 per cent of
its fruit and vegetables, compared with 80 per cent in the US and 70 per
cent in Brazil, the world's largest fruit growers.
Educating farmers to produce exportable crops takes longer than might be
expected. Often Indian seeds need replacing with new varieties bred for
their resistance to disease. Sometimes such seeds can be imported; sometimes
imported seeds must be adapted for Indian conditions - a time-consuming
laboratory job. Similarly, modern watering technologies - such as
drip-feeding techniques developed in the US, Israel and elsewhere - may be
ideal for Indian conditions. But more often than not they need some
alterations. For example, drip-feed systems can carry fertiliser as well as
water to crops - but fertiliser powders can clog the pipework if they are
wrongly prepared.
Unless farmers produce crops of the right quality, investments further along
the food processing pipeline will be worthless. As Mr Khanna of Nijjer says:
'The key to food processing is good links with the farmers'.
Nijjer itself has grown from a tomato farm run in the Punjab by Mr Wasant
Singh Nijjer, who travelled to the US in the 1960s and brought back modern
techniques and high-quality American seeds. After supplying other processors
for over 30 years, Nijjer started processing tomatoes into paste itself in
1991. This year it plans to export half its 5,000-tonne output and earn
about Rs300m ((Pounds 6m) in foreign exchange.
Perhaps, the best way for foreign companies to create such ties with local
farmers is through joint ventures. For example, Nijjer's main rival in
Punjab is a joint venture involving Pepsi, the US food and drinks company
and owner of India's largest tomato paste factory. Other foreign companies
that have invested in food processing include Unilever, the Anglo-Dutch
combine, which this year bought control of Kissan Products, a South Indian
maker of ketchup and food pulp.
An executive at one foreign food processing company says most multinationals
are likely to invest cautiously in Indian agriculture and food processing.
In almost every country, agriculture is prone to political interference, he
says. Foreign companies have to be particularly careful about not raising
nationalist's hackles. However, there are opportunities in India for
investing in downstream processing. India can be a good source of supply,
especially for the fast-growing markets of east Asia, says the executive.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>INZ  India, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
