<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Gold dips below Dollars 370 an
ounce
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOLD TRADED below Dollars 370 a troy ounce on the London bullion market
yesterday after an early bout of selling from the Middle East. Gold futures
were also knocked back sharply by speculative Middle East sales in early
trading on New York's Comex.
London's morning fix of Dollars 370.65 a troy ounce marked a fall of Dollars
4.60 on the previous afternoon fix. But the market recovered some of the
lost ground, fixing at Dollars 371.45 in the afternoon and closing at
Dollars 372.50, a fall of Dollars 2.85 on the day. Trading volume was light.
'The rally has clearly stalled,' said Mr Michael Spriggs, analyst with SG
Warburg. At the end of last month gold touched Dollars 380 a troy ounce in
London, the highest level for nearly two and a half years.
Ms Rhona O'Connell, analyst with Williams de Broe, said the market needed to
consolidate and blow off some of the speculative froth. There had not been
much sign of producers coming into the market with forward sales.
Mr Spriggs said even those who were bullish about the rally should not be
surprised to see some consolidation. There was still no reason in the charts
why the price should not go on to Dollars 400 an ounce.
However, he was a bear of the market, and argued that the recent rise would
prove to be a spike driven by speculative money in the futures and options
markets.
</TEXT>
