<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Italian fraud sparks call for
EC-wide investigation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE EUROPEAN Commission has asked European Community governments to
investigate the possibility of widespread fraud involving surplus stocks of
grain, following the discovery of an Ecu77.7m (Pounds 60m) wheat fraud in
southern Italy.
The Italian agriculture ministry announced at the weekend that a fraud had
been uncovered by 13 commission experts, working with the Italian
authorities in a two-week investigation.
The commission confirmed yesterday that its team had discovered a shortfall
of nearly 260,000 tonnes of durum or hard wheat - worth Ecu77.7m - compared
with the figure declared by AIMA, the Italian government agency that paid
private silos to stock the grain.
The commission's statement coincided with the first day of a two-day
European Parliament hearing on fraud in the Community. Yesterday, Mr John
Tomlinson, a British Labour MEP and member of the Parliament's budgetary
control committee, said fraud could be costing the EC more than Pounds 2bn a
year - 20 times Commission estimates. 'The Commission figure is the tip of
an iceberg - less than Pounds 100m and of that only about eight pence in the
pound recovered,' he said.
Mr Peter Schmidhuber the EC commissioner responsible for fraud prevention,
will address the Parliament's budgetary control committee today.
In its statement on the Italian case, the commission said it had called on
all member states holding surplus grain stocks to carry out 'the appropriate
inquiries', assisted by commission officials.
The commission's inquiry into the Italian fraud centred on stocks held in
Puglia, Basilicata, Campania, Calabria and Sicily, all in the south of the
country.
The commission said yesterday that the exact damage to the EC budget still
had to be worked out, because investigations were continuing into other
grain stocks not covered by the two-week Commission inquiry.
Italy will have to reimburse the community for the sums lost, and the
commission added that any other consequences for EC finances would be
examined as soon as the results of continuing inquiries had been analysed.
The Italian authorities claimed at the weekend that the implications of the
fraud would go well beyond the original value of the shortfall, because
wheat illegally sold on would distort the EC market. Some silos had also
claimed EC subsidies for non-existent purchases of durum wheat, the ministry
alleged.
The Italian involvement in the commission's inquiry is indicative of the new
spirit of co-operation in such investigations under the government of Mr
Carlo Azeglio Ciampi.
</TEXT>
