FT  10 JUN 93 / World Commodities Prices: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COPPER prices fell away from earlier highs in late trading on the LME, but
still ended steady, as did most other metals. Three-month metal made an
abortive attempt to break above Dollars 1,850 a tonne, aided by
option-linked buying. Selling emerged above Dollars 1,840, however, and by
the close the market was back at Dollars 1,834, unchanged from Tuesday.
ALUMINIUM also eased in late trading, pressurised by continued profit taking
and resistance above Dollars 1,180 a tonne for three-month metal. But given
recent investment fund and speculative buying, the market remained on course
for Dollars 1,200, dealers said. London's robusta COFFEE closed with small
gains. The market is caught between underlying buying interest from roasters
and overhead origin selling, particularly from Brazil and Indonesia. London
COCOA closed with marginal losses. Business was dominated by active rolling
forward of positions out of the near July contract into September. Dealers
said there was some talk that the business might have been fund-related.
Talks at the ICCO continued to be monitored. The key issue remains the
eventual dispose of the buffer stock.
Compiled from Reuters
