<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / International Capital Markets: Schiphol Airport flies in the
face of flotation talk
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD VAN DE KROL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   AMSTERDAM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AMSTERDAM'S Schiphol Airport, with a new Triple A/AA1 rating, strong
financial position and international reputation in such areas as efficiency
and duty-free shopping, appears to be a prime candidate to become the next
European airport to be either making or considering a stock market
flotation.
However, the lure of the private sector has no appeal for the airport, even
as it enters the second phase of an ambitious multi-billion guilder, 15-year
project to double in size by the year 2003.
The scale of the investment might have persuaded other airports to look into
attracting outside shareholders, but Schiphol - 76 per cent owned by the
Dutch government, 22 per cent by the city of Amsterdam and 2 per cent by
Rotterdam - is firmly against the idea.
'The answer is simply no,' says Mr Bart van Leeuwen, the airport's finance
director.
True, Schiphol tapped the international bond market last week for the first
time in nearly 30 years, raising Fl 400m (Dollars 222m) towards
consolidating short-term debt and paying for its heavy investment programme.
But the airport, Europe's fifth largest, is happy being 'a private company
owned by the government'.
One key to Schiphol's contentment is that under government ownership it does
not pay corporate tax. Dividend policy is another obvious advantage. For the
past six years, Schiphol has paid an unchanged Fl 60 per share of Fl 1,000
even though operating profit trebled and net profit doubled over the same
period.
This minimal dividend has freed cash-flow for a Fl 4.5bn investment
programme launched in 1989 and due for completion in the year 2003.
Privatised airports, such as BAA in the UK or Vienna airport in Austria,
must generate cash to satisfy their shareholders and to plough back into
their operations, Mr Leeuwen says.
Schiphol's firm opposition to privatisation, which is shared by its three
public-sector owners, does not mean that it plans to remain aloof from the
international capital market.
Last week's 7-year 6.75 per cent Eurobond, led by ING Bank and supported by
Schiphol's AAA rating from Standard &amp; Poor's and AA1 from Moody's, could be
followed by bonds in future years, al-though Mr van Leeuwen is keeping an
open mind. Until now, Schiphol has financed investments almost exclusively
through private placements and internal cash flow.
Its finances were lifted by its record performance in 1992, with net profit
rising by 55 per cent to Fl 90m. This is in contrast to the loss-making KLM
Royal Dutch Airlines, which accounts for nearly half of Schiphol's revenue
and half its aircraft movements.
Reflecting the difficult straits of the world's airlines, Schiphol raised
its landing charges by just 1.6 per cent in April instead of the 3 per cent
rate by which it would normally have increased charges to keep up with
inflation.
The first five-year phase of Schiphol's 15-year investment programme was
completed last month, when the airport opened a Fl 550m extension to its
existing terminal building, raising passenger capacity to 27m a year from
19m.
According to the airport's investment projections, its financial obligations
will start to exceed free cash flow around the turn of the century, when
Schiphol is hoping to build a fifth runway to lift its capacity to more than
100 aircraft movements an hour from the current 70 to 80.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>NLZ  Netherlands, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
