FT  10 JUN 93 / International Company News: Enso-Gutzeit to expand in east
Germany
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LEIPZIG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ENSO-GUTZEIT, one of Finland's largest paper makers, yesterday announced
plans to build a DM800m (Dollars 493m) recycling plant in the eastern German
state of Saxony, the biggest single foreign investment so far in the region.
In a move aimed at expanding into the German market, and later into eastern
Europe, the group will use the green-field site primarily for recycling, and
will target the product for the growing newspaper market in eastern Germany.
Germany already accounts for 15 per cent of the group's net sales, which
last year totalled FM10.2bn (Dollars 1.86bn).
The plant, situated east of Leipzig, one of the fastest-growing industrial
centres among the five new eastern states, will start operating in September
1994 with an initial workforce of 300 people.
Mr Jukka Hamala, director of Enso, said the decision to locate in Saxony was
prompted by the region's proximity to southern Germany, the Czech Republic,
and other countries in eastern Europe.
'We are in the middle of one of the fastest-growing markets in Europe,' he
said, adding that the group had wanted to enter the recycling market for
some time, but could not obtain enough capacity from the small Finnish
market.
Mr Kai Korkonen, managing director of Sachsen Papier Eilenburg, the company
set up to run the plant, said it would have a production capacity of 280,000
tons a year.
The government of Saxony, led by Mr Kurt Biedenkopf, had lobbied hard to
attract Enso. 'Western Germany could take a leaf out of our book. Saxony is
determined to attract foreign investors and make the region a highly
competitive market.' Mr Biedenkopf, an economist and one of the most dynamic
prime ministers in the eastern German state, also said the investment by
Enso could persuade other foreign investors to settle in Saxony, and create
jobs.
