<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / International Company News: Rembrandt results show little
change
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
REMBRANDT Group, the South African tobacco-based conglomerate, produced
earnings per share virtually unchanged at 182.1 cents for the year ended
March as weak performances from industrial interests offset growth on the
tobacco and banking side.
The results were broadly in line with market expectations, although
disappointing by the standards of Rembrandt - one of the largest and most
successful companies in the country. Rembrandt is controlled by the Rupert
family, which also controls the Swiss-based tobacco and luxury goods group
Richemont.
The group is stepping up its dividend by 11 per cent to 36.2 cents a share,
against the 32.6 cents paid for 1991-92.
Income before tax rose to R1.24bn (Dollars 269m) from R1.17bn.
Tobacco, where the group has a market share of about 80 per cent, normally
contributes about 40 per cent of bottom line earnings. Analysts believe that
on the published figures, attributable income from tobacco probably rose by
14-15 per cent despite an estimated 3 per cent decline in volumes.
Offsetting this werepoor figures from Huntcor, the industrial subsidiary
with food and forestry interests. Huntcor's attributable profits fell by 65
per cent, mainly on account of a R77m loss at Rainbow Chickens. Metkor and
Dorbyl, other industrial investments in the group, also performed poorly.
Aside from tobacco, and industrial interests - which account for about 10
per cent - some 18 per cent of group earnings come from Genbeheer, the
holding company of Gencor, in which Rembrandt has a 25.2 per cent stake.
Earnings at ABSA, the country's largest banking group, which contributes
about 7 per cent of Rembrandt's earnings, rose by 12 per cent.
