<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / International Company News: Premier earnings up 16% despite
difficult conditions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PREMIER Group, the South African food, pharmaceuticals and retail group,
overcame difficult trading conditions last year to record a 16 per cent
increase in earnings per share to 283 cents.
The results reflect a better than expected performance from Metro Cash and
Carry, the food distributor and a substantial improvement in earnings from
Premier Pharmaceuticals.
Contributions from the group's core food division were flat as the drought
and deteriorating socio-political conditions put margins under pressure. On
the retail side, CNA Gallo performed slightly better and Clicks recorded
good growth.
Turnover rose 3 per cent to R10.1bn (Dollars 3.16bn) with trading profit 4
per cent higher at R438.9m. A decline in the interest bill to R23.6m from
R58m boosted pre-tax profits, which rose by 15 per cent to R415.3m.
A lower tax charge and higher dividend income and equity accounted earnings
helped lift net profits by 23 per cent to R233.8m. The dividend is going up
from 81 cents a share to 94 cents.
Mr Peter Wrighton, the chairman, said the group was planning for real growth
in the year ahead. This assumed a political settlement, a better performance
from the food division and CNA Gallo, first time contributions from Bonnita
and UPD, and other operations staying on course.
Mr Wrighton stressed that last year, ending April, was characterised by a
number of acquisitions and disposals.
Premier paid R144m for a 39 per cent interest in Bonnita Holdings, South
Africa's second largest producer of milk based products; increased its
shareholdings in Premier Pharmaceuticals, Clicks and Metro; and formed
United Pharmaceutical Distributors, a wholesale distribution company in
which Premier has an effective 40 per cent stake.
The chairman said the group had also substantially increased its investment
in people development to over R20m a year.
