<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / International Company News: Kleinwort settles suit with US
broker
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE LAWSUIT filed by Wall Street securities house PaineWebber against the UK
investment bank Kleinwort Benson alleging that two of its former executives
who defected in April to Kleinwort's US operation had improperly lured away
clients, employees and confidential information has been settled.
The suit was filed on April 29 after Mr Stephen Canter, president and chief
executive of PaineWebber's investment management subsidiary Mitchell
Hutchins Institutional Investors (MHII), and Mr Emad Zikry, the firm's
managing director of fixed income and quantitative investing, left the firm
for Kleinwort Benson International Investment in New York. Following their
departure, several other MHII executives also joined them at Kleinwort.
At the time, PaineWebber said the two had recruited other MHII employees
while still at the firm and used confidential and proprietary client
information to solicit MHII clients.
As part of its settlement with Kleinwort, however, MHII acknowledged that
'after completing expedited pre-trial discovery proceedings, it has
discovered no evidence that either Mr Canter or Mr Zikry, while in the
employ of MHII, solicited any client or any employee of MHII to leave MHII
or took any property belonging to MHII'.
Both sides expressed satisfaction with the outcome, the full terms of which
were not disclosed.
