<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / International Company News: Decision time for O&amp;Y in the US
 -A row threatens to derail Dollars 5.3bn debt talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Cyrus Vance is due to tell a New York judge today whether he has had more
success in brokering a peace agreement among squabbling creditors of Olympia
&amp; York than he had among the warring factions of Bosnia.
In a business version of shuttle diplomacy, the former US secretary of state
has spent the past 10 days meeting the various protagonists separately. He
has asked them not to talk to the press or to each other. One of the parties
predicts that he is more likely to submit a progress report today than the
terms of a full peace settlement.
Mr Vance was approached in a last-ditch effort to break a deadlock over the
appointment of a new board of directors for Olympia &amp; York Real Estate USA,
the crippled Canadian developer's 80 per cent owned US subsidiary.
The row over the directors has wider ramifications, however, for the
company, one arm of O&amp;Y which has so far managed to avoid the protection of
a bankruptcy court.
In particular, it threatens to derail painstaking negotiations to
restructure USDollars 5.3bn in debt owed by the US subsidiary to about two
dozen separate groups of lenders.
The US unit's secured creditors are backing demands by its management for
greater autonomy from Olympia &amp; York Developments (OYDL), the Toronto-based
parent company. OYDL emerged from bankruptcy protection last month, and is
now run by a court-appointed administrator.
The administrator, Mr Robert Lowe, an insolvency specialist in the Toronto
office of Coopers &amp; Lybrand, is assisted by a five-member 'monitoring
committee' representing OYDL's unsecured shareholders. The committee is
chaired by Hongkong &amp; Shanghai Banking Corporation, OYDL's biggest creditor.
The US subsidiary, led by former New York deputy mayor John Zuccotti,
believes that a degree of independence from Toronto would expedite the US
restructuring plan, as well as maintain the stability and values of O&amp;Y's US
properties, which include the 7.6m sq ft World Financial Centre in lower
Manhattan.
Central to the demands of the US unit and its creditors is the inclusion of
three independent directors, based in New York, on the board of O&amp;Y USA.
Mr Zuccotti and the secured lenders have accused the administrator and the
monitoring committee in Toronto of stonewalling the appointment of an
independent board.
According to an affidavit submitted by Mr Zuccotti last week, the committee
and the administrator also do not see eye to eye over which of them controls
the US subsidiary. Mr Zuccotti said that this situation has made it
'virtually impossible for me to properly perform my duties'.
Spokesmen for both the monitoring committee and the administrator have
denied Mr Zuccotti's assertion.
With no US board in place to take decisions or set policy guidelines, the
debt talks have ground to a halt.
A lawyer for one group of Japanese creditors says that a successful debt
plan is 'almost impossible' without a resolution of the corporate governance
issues.
The dispute over the independence of the US board also appears to be part of
an inevitable jockeying for position among different classes of creditors.
An official at one bank involved in the negotiations notes that the present
market value of the US properties is not enough to cover even the claims of
fully-secured creditors.
They will be forced to take 'a pretty sizeable haircut,' he predicts.
Matters are complicated however, by the overlapping interests of some
creditors.
Two secured creditors of the US operations, Sanwa Bank and Canadian Imperial
Bank of Commerce, are also members of the Canadian monitoring committee of
unsecured creditors. CIBC and Sanwa have opposed moves by the rest of the
committee to keep control of the US board in Canada.
Citibank, which has spearheaded efforts by the US creditors to obtain
greater independence for O&amp;Y USA, was co-chairman of the Canadian unsecured
creditors committee which approved the parent company's restructuring plan.
One banker accuses Citibank of displaying 'a degree of schizophrenia'.
For his part, Mr Lowe noted in a statement last month that he has a
fiduciary responsibility to about 100 international creditors of OYDL, many
of them in the US. The tangled negotiations raise the prospect that O&amp;Y USA
may, in the end, be unable to avoid the same fate as its parent.
An official at one secured lender predicts that the wrangling among
creditors will eventually force all the group's US properties into the
bankruptcy courts.
Mr Zuccotti noted in his recent affidavit that 'the expense and complexity
is multiplying . . . The process that has emerged has erected barriers to
communication, presents a constant threat to credibility, and provides an
image of apparent confusion in decision-making.'
But O&amp;Y USA also insists that talks with several creditor groups have made
substantial progress. A number of properties have already been sold or
handed over to creditors. There are plans to sell others, notably a
33-storey building in Portland, Oregon.
A spokesman says the company is 'quite confident that it has a very good
shot at accomplishing (a debt-restructuring)' if the dispute over the board
of directors can be settled.
</TEXT>
