<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / International Company News: Disposal clears Uni for cash
call
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN FOSSLI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   OSLO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
UNI STOREBRAND, Norway's largest insurance group, is to be re-listed on the
Oslo Stock Exchange within two weeks. It will then be released from the grip
of public administrators in August, company officials said yesterday.
The disposal on Tuesday of Uni Holding's 25 per cent stake in Skandia, the
big Swedish insurance group, was the last step in a difficult process to
facilitate a NKr4.3bn (Dollars 627m) recapitalisation of the group.
A fully-underwritten share offer will raise NKr2.8bn, while a bond issue
will generate the remaining NKr1.5bn. A prospectus for the issue of 208m new
shares, to be sent to 115,000 former Uni shareholders, is about to be
finalised. The shares in the rights issue will be priced a NKr10 each.
Norway's finance ministry had demanded the disposal of the Skandia stake
before it would approve the plan.
Uni collapsed last August under the weight of NKr3.8bn in short-term debt
accrued to finance the acquisition of a NKr4.7bn, 28.3 per cent Skandia
shareholding. Uni, together with Hafnia, the Danish insurance company,
jointly launched a failed raid on Skandia, which almost resulted in the
demise of both companies. Uni and Hafnia disposed of their respective
Skandia shareholdings in a deal valued at SKr3.2bn (Dollars 441m).
Skandia warmly welcomed news of the share placing, saying it brought
stability to its ownership base and 'a strong position in the market for
future success'. Mr Bjorn Wolrath, Skandia chief executive, said: 'This
means that uncertainty concerning the ownership issue, which has prevailed
for nearly three years, has at last been resolved.'
Uni sold 18.96m shares at SKr100 a share, or a total of NKr1.77bn, while
Hafnia got SKr110 a share.
At the end of March, Uni Holding's 25 per cent Skandia stake was booked at a
value of NKr1.57bn, which means it will book a gain on the disposal of an
estimated NKr200m. Uni's life insurance business still holds a 3.3 per cent
stake in Skandia, or 2.5m shares.
Skandia has rebuffed two assaults since 1990 - the first from Skandinaviska
Enskilda Banken, the second from Hafnia and Uni Storebrand - but saw its
share price plunge from around SKr220 to a low of SKr45 in the process.
Lex, Page 20
