<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / UK Company News: Demerger appears successful as Racal
Electronics recovers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RECOVERY in Racal Electronics pre-tax profits, from Pounds 16.1m to
Pounds 51.5m, is the latest evidence Sir Ernest Harrison's demerger of the
group has added to shareholders' value.
The group may have benefitted from a general rise in the market since
Williams Holdings launched its hostile bid in 1991. But the turnround at
Racal and - surprises apart - the continuing strong performance at Chubb
which reports today, suggests that had the bid succeeded, it would have been
a deal of a lifetime for Williams.
This is not to say Racal has left its troubles behind. An overwhelming
Pounds 370.6m of sales - 39 per cent of group turnover - still comes from
data communications.
Margins may have recovered to 3.4 per cent from less than 0.5 per cent last
year. But rather like the personal computer market, this industry remains
fiercely competit-ive with margins and prices permanently under press-ure.
Adding two more percentage points of margin over the next two years as the
group has targetted, will have an impact on profits and earnings. But data
communications is hardly an area likely to generate strong long term growth
once that margin recovery has been achieved.
Elsewhere Racal remains a mixed bag of businesses which analysts say still
appears to lack clear strategic direction. Some businesses, like military
radio, in-flight telephony and area data networks would appear to have
strong long term potential.
There again, Redac the computer aided design business, continues to
disappoint in the short term and will continue to make losses this year, the
problem now being in the tough Japanese market.
Racal has sharply increased cash flow and hopes to do the same this year in
the data communications area, which should lead to further strengthening of
the balance sheet.
Recovery should lead to profits this year of Pounds 63m, giving earnings of
13.8p, rising to Pounds 72.5m or 16p next year.
This puts Racal's prospective earnings mulitiple on a 15 per cent premium to
the market this year, which given the tough nature of some of its markets,
seems high enough.
</TEXT>
