<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / UK Company News: Cape cut by lower interest income
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CAPE, the industrial services and building products group controlled by
Charter Consolidated, yesterday reported a slight fall in profits because of
lower interest income.
Pre-tax profits dropped from Pounds 12.4m to Pounds 11.9m in the year to
March 31. Mr Jeffrey Herbert, chairman, said the results were satisfactory
given recession in the building industry. At the interim stage, profits fell
9 per cent to Pounds 6.52m.
Interest income fell from Pounds 1.08m to just Pounds 11,000. The company
said cash resources plunged Pounds 12m because of working capital needs and
capital expenditure.
Turnover increased 21 per cent to Pounds 245.2m, helped by acquisitions and
strong overseas sales. The latter rose by more than a third and now account
for 44 per cent of turnover, compared to 39 per cent a year ago.
Operating profits gained 2 per cent to Pounds 13.2m and were depressed by
losses at two building products companies. The building and architectural
products division saw profits fall from Pounds 6.88m to Pounds 6.48m while
industrial services increased 10 per cent to Pounds 6.69m.
Acquisitions, which included the purchase in December from William Baird of
contractor Darchem, contributed Pounds 4.9m of sales and Pounds 211,000 of
operating profits.
Earnings fell from 15.3p to 14.9p. The final dividend is 7.75p for a total
of 10.75p (10.5p).
</TEXT>
