<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / UK Company News: Airsprung's 22% growth prompts share price
rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES IN Airsprung Furniture Group rose 11p to a record 518p after
Britain's second-largest bed manufacturer reported a 22 per cent increase in
pre-tax profits to Pounds 6m.
Sales rose by 12.9 per cent to Pounds 65.6m in the year to March 31 and
operating profit was 14.9 per cent higher at Pounds 5.8m.
The group said its beds division, which accounts for 50 per cent of
turnover, had performed well. Sales and profits were well ahead of last
year, although it suffered from a shortage of demand at the top of its
range.
The upholstery division, which accounts for 30 per cent of turnover,
increased sales, but severe competition had substantially reduced margins in
the manufacturing companies.
The pine furniture division, which produces 15 per cent of turnover, showed
a substantial improvement in both sales and profits.
Last month Mr Michael Coppel was appointed joint chairman alongside Mr John
Yates, 77, whose family controls 42 per cent of Airsprung. Mr John Pierce
replaced Mr Coppel as chief executive, Mr John Mack became chairman of the
upholstery division and Mr Peter Ziemnak was appointed managing director of
Airsprung Beds. Mr Coppel said those appointments would ensure continuity of
management into the next century.
The group said: 'The current year seems to be fraught with uncertainties.
However, we have planned for further growth and are confident that this will
be achieved provided we get a reasonable climate in which to operate.'
Earnings per share fell from 33.1p to 31.4p, although the previous year's
figure benefited from the release of deferred tax previously provided, worth
6.5p per share. A final dividend of 5.85p gives a total for the year of 9p
(7.5p), a rise of 20 per cent.
</TEXT>
