FT  10 JUN 93 / UK Company News: Shareholders attack Saatchi's failure to
pay dividend
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHAREHOLDERS at Saatchi &amp; Saatchi's annual meeting yesterday expressed
dissatisfaction at the advertising group's failure to pay a 1992 dividend,
though a Pounds 73m rights issue announced on May 19 received overwhelming
approval at the extraordinary meeting which followed.
One shareholder criticised director Mr Charles Saatchi for again failing to
attend the meeting while receiving what the speaker described as 'the
infamous salary' of Pounds 312,500.
Mr Saatchi, like his brother Maurice, chairman of the company, was entitled
to twice that figure, but agreed to waive half.
The two men have sold the rights to buy 502,417 ordinary shares, raising
Pounds 145,700, which they will use to subscribe for 116,718 of the shares
in the rights issue.
Three other company directors have also disposed of ordinary share rights.
After the June 11 rights issue the brothers will have a combined holding of
1.7m shares. The company is offering 59.4m new ordinary shares at 130p each,
on the basis of 10 new shares for every 27 held.
Mr Charles Scott, chief executive, told the meeting he expected the company
to return to dividend payments for 1994.
