<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / UK Company News: Sizeable premium expected for Quayle Munro
debut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRADING IN Quayle Munro Holdings, a small Edinburgh-based merchant bank with
a portfolio of holdings in unquoted companies, begins on the main market
today.
Analysts believe that the shares will rise to a substantial premium.
The bank is coming to the market via an introduction by Williams de Broe.
It follows a reverse takeover of Quayle Munro by East of Scotland Industrial
Investments, the unquoted investment company which Quayle Munro manages.
The shares will be quoted initially at 118p per share, which implies a
market capitalisation of Pounds 4.74m. The company will have net worth of
about Pounds 6m, of which Pounds 4m is in unquoted investments and the rest
in cash and listed securities.
Analysts believe that the discount to net asset value will narrow and that
investors will also be attracted by the high dividend yield. The company
will pay an interim dividend of 3p next month and another 3p in October; and
in future will pay interim and final dividends in a ratio of one third to
two thirds.
Assuming the interim dividend is maintained that implies that next year's
final will be 6p, making 9p in all. Analysts believe the shares could go to
a premium of more than 20 per cent.
Quayle Munro was founded in 1983 by Mr Ian Jones and Mr Michael Munro. It
advises quoted companies such as Shanks &amp; McEwan, the waste disposal group,
and Pittencrieff, the oil company.
It worked for the Scottish Office on privatising the Scottish Bus Group and
recently advised it on the possible privatisation of Scotland's water and
sewerage services.
Mr Jones, chief executive, explained that one aim of the transaction with
East of Scotland Industrial Investments was to give shareholders an exit
route at a smaller discount to net asset value than was available under the
old structure. The deal involves repaying about Pounds 10m of capital.
'Quayle Munro will be unusual in being both a merchant bank and an
investment banking house,' said Mr Jones. 'There will be two kinds of play -
fee income and capital performance.'
</TEXT>
