<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / UK Company News: Jump in interest reins in Greencore
progress to 5%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GREENCORE, the Irish sugar, milling and malting group, reported a 5 per cent
increase in pre-tax profits to IPounds 17.1m (Pounds 16.8m) on turnover up 7
per cent, for the half year to March 26.
Operating profits for the period increased by 15 per cent to IPounds 23.4m,
but a 50 per cent jump in interest charges to IPounds 6.4m due to last
autumn's currency crisis cut into the improved profit margins.
Mr Kevin O'Sullivan, chief financial officer, said that the increased
interest charge 'has been a short-term phenomena which will not affect
future results'.
Operating profits improved substantially in the sugar and other food
divisions, while the agribusiness division suffered a squeeze on margins as
CAP reforms put downward pressure on prices for fertilisers and animal
feeds. Agribusiness turnover, however, increased by 8 per cent.
Earnings per share rose 1p to 17p, while the interim dividend goes up 10 per
cent to 3.3p.
The result was slightly ahead of market expectations, and the shares
strengthened to 295p.
The company said that the impact of green currency realignments under EC
agricultural policy and the stabilisation of interest and exchange rates
'will have a net favourable impact on our second half trading figures and
for 1993-94 as a whole'.
