<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Hanson power provokes concern
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HANSON, the Anglo-US conglomerate, is facing growing shareholder concern
over its proposals to give its chairman, Lord Hanson, greater control over
its annual general meetings.
The proposals, which need the support of 75 per cent of investors, will be
put to an extraordinary general meeting on June 25. Some of Hanson's biggest
shareholders have raised the matter with the National Association of Pension
Funds.
Mr John Rogers, secretary of the association's investment committee said: 'A
number of large institutional shareholders are concerned about the proposals
and have raised the matter with Hanson.'
The EGM was called to approve a scrip dividend plan which requires the
modification of the company's articles of association.
Lord Hanson, in a letter to shareholders, said: 'At the same time we are
proposing to introduce a number of other alterations to the articles.' These
are 'mainly designed to facilitate the orderly conduct of meetings' by
giving the chairman of Hanson's AGM (which is always Lord Hanson) greater
powers.
Under the new articles, the chairman would be able to prevent shareholders
speaking more than once on any item of business; prevent a member from
speaking if it was 'prejudicing the orderly conduct' and reject any demand
for polls which in his opinion is 'irrelevant, or vexatious to, or
inconsistent with, the business of the meeting'.
Shareholders would no longer be able to nominate directors unless supported
by 10 per cent of the share capital.
Mr Derek Bonham, chief executive, said: 'We are tidying up matters by
helping improve the efficiency of our meetings.'
Some of the proposed changes, such as the retirement by rotation and
re-election of directors, are supported by shareholders, as is the scrip
dividend plan.
However, some big shareholders, including Postel, the UK's biggest pension
fund, are seeking meetings with Hanson to discuss the proposed changes.
Ms Anne Simpson, joint managing director of the Pension Investment Research
Consultants, said: 'The spirit of Cadbury needs to be taken on board by
extending shareholders rights not by restricting them.'
London SE, Page 42
</TEXT>
