<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Steps agreed to defend Moslems: US and EC still divided on
strategy for ending conflict in Bosnia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LUXEMBOURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US and the European Community yesterday agreed on minimum steps to
defend the besieged Moslem population in Bosnia and pledged to reinforce
efforts to prevent the conflict from escalating into a wider Balkan war.
But after a meeting of EC foreign ministers and Mr Warren Christopher, US
secretary of state, profound divisions remained over a wider strategy to end
the conflict in Bosnia and reverse Serbian and Croatian territorial gains.
The divisions became explicit during a news conference at the end of the
Luxembourg meeting originally intended to provide a show of western alliance
unity ahead of the Nato summit which opens today in Athens.
Mr Niels Helvig Petersen, foreign minister of Denmark, which holds the
rotating EC presidency, said there was no point in finger-pointing. But he
promptly laid bare transatlantic differences by saying the Vance-Owen peace
plan was 'the centrepiece of EC policy' towards Bosnia.
In response, Mr Christopher declined to endorse the Vance-Owen plan,
declaring only that the UN-EC plan had 'many positive aspects' which could
be built on. He also said that the US had not abandoned its preferred option
of arming the Bosnia Moslems - despite a French statement that this was 'a
policy of despair'.
More fundamentally, Mr Christopher's references to the Vance-Owen 'process'
left the impression that the US believes the original EC-UN plan to divide
Bosnia into 10 semi-autonomous provinces is no longer viable because of
Serbian and Croatian territorial gains in Bosnia.
This assessment gained tacit support in Luxembourg, with some delegations,
notably Belgium, calling for a basic reassessment of the Bosnian conflict.
A new approach would include sanctions against Croatia to deter further
aggression and a possible redrawing of the Vance-Owen map, an EC official
said.
It would also reinforce what Mr Christopher identified as a prime US goal -
the territorial integrity of Serbia's province of Kosovo and the former
Yugoslav republic of Macedonia.
The immediate requirement is to plug the gaps in the UN peacekeeping force
and give effect to last week's UN resolution to defend the six UN 'safe
areas'. Both the EC and UN are seeking recruits from Moslem countries,
Scandinavia and the former Soviet Union, but EC diplomats said it would take
at least six weeks to put the force of about 5,000 troops together.
Mr Christopher repeated that the US was not willing to provide ground-forces
in the 'safe areas' operation. He rebutted criticism from Lord Owen, the EC
peace negotiator, saying that the US would provide troops only after the
warring parties have reached a watertight political settlement.
The limited nature of US military engagement became clear when Mr
Christopher avoided a commitment to send aircraft to defend civilians.
Milosevic pressed on sanctions, Page 2
Editorial Comment, Page 19
</TEXT>
