<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / The Lex Column: Johnson Matthey
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A cursory glance at Johnson Matthey's share price suggests the company has
successfully detached itself from swings in metals prices. But with Charter
Consolidated's stake now in friendly hands, progress from here on will have
to come without the benefit of bid speculation. Johnson has also exhausted
big restructuring provisions taken in 1990. Although cost savings of Pounds
25m a year suggest the money has been well spent, profits growth must be
found elsewhere.
Strong metals prices cannot be counted on for assistance. The platinum price
is healthy enough, but rhodium remains painfully weak. Bargain basement
prices should eventually lead to a new round of stock-building, but there is
no sign of that yet. Meanwhile, Johnson's precious metals division remains
in the doldrums. Promising positions in electronics materials and medicine
are being built, but it is hard to avoid the conclusion that demand for its
catalytic converters is getting a timely boost from European legislation on
vehicle emissions.
Thanks to the new rules Johnson expects to produce more converters in Europe
this year, even allowing for a slide in new car sales. Tougher environmental
standards in the US are also good for business. Assuming margins can be
defended against the tough new breed of purchasing managers at Volkswagen
and elsewhere, at least modest profits growth from converters looks assured.
But it will take a rising trend in car sales before Johnson is really
insulated from the metals cycle.
</TEXT>
