<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / The Lex Column: Northern Foods
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The market may fret about the death of the brand but Northern Foods, at
least, shows that there can be life beyond the grave for food manufacturers.
Acting as the hired hand for the big supermarket chains can be a healthy
enough business as Northern's 21 per cent advance in annual pre-tax profits
demonstrates. The company's extensive rationalisation programme may even
enable trading margins to climb above 10 per cent this year. Few food
manufacturers, branded or otherwise, can boast that.
Such considerations make Northern's 16 per cent underperformance against the
food manufacturing sector over the past year rather puzzling. The company's
earnings growth may tend towards the respectable rather than racy, but a
forward multiple of under 12 hardly demands a lot.
Northern's rating has been depressed by the uncertainties in the dairy
market ahead of the reform of the Milk Marketing Board. With half its
profits flowing from its dairy businesses, Northern has a critical interest
in the outcome. But although the industry's profitability may well decline
over the long run, Northern should still be able to skim off a fair amount
of cream. Unlike many commodity food businesses, milk may retain some
premium for quality. The challenge facing Northern will be to recycle its
cash flow quickly enough into higher margin businesses to ensure continued
growth. The 51 per cent rise in operating profits from convenience foods
suggests it could well be up to the mark.
</TEXT>
