<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / The Lex Column: Lamont's last lament
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Lamont's appeal for the government to lead has struck a blow at the prime
minister, but looks a little rich coming from a victim of events. The
markets' most likely response to such homilies is a hollow laugh -
especially since the City has seen little leadership from the government
since the general election. Calls for an independent Bank of England will
get equally short shrift, given that Mr Major looks unlikely to act on the
suggestion.
What is perhaps more influential is final confirmation from Mr Major
yesterday that the UK is unlikely to re-enter the ERM during this
parliament. That leaves the policy focus unequivocally on domestic concerns,
and by implication on the PSBR. It may be that such concentration will
eventually prove misguided, if a significant part of the deficit proves
cyclical. Yet that will depend upon how far the UK economy is running below
capacity, and the extent to which the tax base has been eroded or made more
volatile by the tax reforms of the 1980s. Such judgments are extremely
difficult to make. The government is therefore forced back on to some kind
of medium-term framework for balancing the public finances that carries
credibility with the markets. This, rather than headline spending cuts,
should be the focus of the current review.
Still, if the new chancellor decides to use his political clout to cut
spending significantly, there may be an interest rate cut to soften the
blow. By the autumn, however, the strength of the economy may make lower
rates unnecessary. And the market's hopes of an earlier cut look distinctly
misplaced.
</TEXT>
