<PROFILE>_AN-DFJB6ADOFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930610
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Leading Article: Student fees
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MR TIM Boswell, the higher education minister, has distanced the government
from the decision by the London School of Economics to charge students an
extra tuition fee of up to Pounds 1,000. The move had not been initiated by
him or the education department, he said, and there were no plans to
encourage other universities to follow suit. The minister doth protest too
much, for it is only a few weeks since the government cut the tuition fees
it pays for classroom-based courses from Pounds 1,850 to Pounds 1,300. Other
universities may soon follow the LSE's lead to recoup the cut in income.
If they do, it will be only the first step in an irresistible move to compel
students to pay a greater share of the bill for higher education. The
government target is for one in three school-leavers to enter university by
the year 2000, two-thirds more than in 1990. The Committee of
Vice-Chancellors and Principals recently said that investment of well over
Pounds 3bn would be needed to achieve this. The extra student grants and
fees could add up to another Pounds 1bn. Such sums are unlikely to be
available from a Treasury already struggling to contain public sector
borrowing.
There may be scope to save money by ending subsidies for students who wish
to study away from home. Since there are now more than 80 universities, most
could find a suitable course close to home. Universities might be able to
raise more from appeals, sponsorship and other sources. They could make more
productive use of their facilities by adopting a semester system. And they
could be given greater freedom to borrow against their assets, as
recommended by the Pearce report.
But there will remain a funding gap which it is unreasonable to expect the
taxpayer to bridge. The students who benefit from higher education should
make a contribution to the fees, with appropriate help for those from
low-income households. Such a system would allow the government to give
additional support to national priority subjects such as science and
technology through higher subsidies. It would also encourage students to
make more rational decisions about their courses, since they would bear more
of the costs as well as reaping the benefits.
Moving towards a greater element of funding from students would require an
overhaul of the student loan system, however. Students would need to be able
to borrow larger sums over longer periods in this new world of higher
education. Lending against human capital is a risky business for banks and
institutions, since it can be hard to collect debts and trace debtors. The
government could help by collecting repayments through a graduate surcharge
on national insurance contributions. Rather than disowning the LSE's
initiative, ministers should be looking at ways of extending it if the
promised expansion in higher education is not to founder through lack of
funds.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8299 Schools and Educational Services, NEC.
    P8221 Colleges and Universities.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
