<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Observer: Aunty George?
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Who's to be next chairman of the BBC governors? Even though Marmaduke
Hussey's term runs until November 1996, there are persistent rumours he will
go sooner rather than later.
With his vice-chairman, Lord Barnett, standing down at the end of next
month, the next chairman could well be among the clutch of new governors to
be enshrined shortly. True, judging by how often Bosnian peace envoy Lord
Owen's name is bandied about, the government can hardly have overlooked him.
But there's a much more obvious candidate - businessman Sir George Russell.
Better known as chairman of the Independent Television Commission than head
of building products group Marley, he'll probably have time on his hands
next year. His term as chairman of the ITC runs out in 18 months or so, and
he seems intent on bowing out of Marley.
If the government wanted Aunty led by a business type, as opposed to a
political has-been, then Russell seems an ideal fit to take on the BBC
poisoned chalice. His commercial acumen is not in doubt, and he made a fair
stab at sorting out the ministerially created mess over the ITV franchise
awards. He is also a former chairman of Independent Television News and
deputy chairman of Channel 4.
Nor should the fact that he works for the opposition be a problem. Lord Hill
of Luton was chairman of the Independent Television Authority before he took
over the BBC chair. If Sir George were to be offered the job, it would be
good news for Bob Phillis,the current BBC deputy director general. A few
years ago Russell helped Phillis become chief executive of ITN.
</TEXT>
