<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Letter: Strong case for government to help Maxwell victims
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr COLIN CORNWALL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, You are right to remind readers that fines imposed on Invesco MIM by
Imro do not reduce the need to review pension fund stewardship and City
regulation generally. Nor do they alleviate the plight of Maxwell's victims
('Maxwell: keeping the issues in sight', June 7).
In the same edition, your report,'Maxwell pensions shortfall cut to less
than Pounds 100m', suggests that substantial progress has been made towards
meeting the shortfall in the Maxwell pension schemes. This view, which
reflects comments that I have heard elsewhere, is misconceived.
The misappropriations from the Common Investment Fund (CIF) were in the
region of Pounds 250m-Pounds 300m. The Mirror Group Pension Scheme's share
of these losses is roughly one half. In addition, more than Pounds 100m was
misappropriated from the Mirror scheme's own funds outside the CIF. Thus,
the Mirror scheme alone has lost more than Pounds 200m. The other Maxwell
schemes taken together have also lost sums approaching Pounds 200m.
One aspect of the more optimistic assessments that I have seen is that they
include a suggestion that it is not necessary to recover all the missing
funds since the Maxwell schemes used to have actuarial surpluses. However,
this ignores the fact that, in the end, benefits will have to be secured
either (a) by the purchase of annuities and deferred annuities from a life
office, or (b) by running down the schemes over the lifetime of their
members and therefore pursuing a restrictive policy of investment in fixed
interest securities that as nearly as possible match the scheme's
crystallised liabilities.
In both cases, the funds required to secure the benefits will be greater
than the provision normally appropriate in a healthy, on-going scheme, and
so the former surpluses will be needed to meet the additional cost. It is
nowadays common for a scheme to have an actuarial surplus in relation to its
on-going funding target but to be in deficit on winding up.
The liquidators of Bishopsgate Investment Management (responsible for the
CIF) and the trustees of the Maxwell pension schemes have traced most of the
missing funds, but finding out where they went is not the same as getting
them back. So far, the only significant asset recovery has been the return
of some 25m Teva shares to the CIF by National Westminster Bank a year ago,
which is taken into account in the above figures.
So far support from the government's Pounds 2.5m 'drip feed' and now from
Sir John Cuckney's Pounds 6.25m Maxwell Pensioners Trust has ensured that
Maxwell pensioners have generally continued to receive their pensions in
full, but this support will run out in about three years. Unless there have
been very substantial asset recoveries by then, thousands of current
pensioners will be in danger of suffering a reduction in their benefits and
thousands of prospective pensioners could lose their benefits altogether.
Employees and former employees of MGN are not counted among these victims,
since MGN has undertaken almost entirely to refinance their benefits over a
period of up to 14 years. This commitment resulted in a provision in MGN's
accounts of roughly Pounds 200m.
Thus MGN shareholders are also Maxwell victims. Of course, the actual cost
to MGN will depend on the level of asset recoveries achieved by the pension
schemes.
The Mirror scheme trustees are pursuing legal actions for the return of
Pounds 88m, and for unliquidated damages for losses generally, against
Invesco MIM, Capel Cure Myers, Lehman Bros, Bank of America and Credit
Suisse. So far, these are the only legal proceedings issued against
financial institutions or professional advisers either by Maxwell scheme
trustees or by the BIM liquidators. Many other possible claims are still
being examined and there is in prospect a welter of litigation on a massive
scale.
I therefore welcome your call on the regulators to use all powers available
to them to encourage or impose a global settlement, and would much prefer to
obtain redress for the Maxwell victims in this way than by litigation - so
long as the amounts are realistic.
Finally, with a total shortfall in excess of Pounds 400m, it seems unlikely
that a global settlement or maximum recovery through litigation will fully
compensate the Maxwell victims. In view of the failure of law and regulation
to which you refer, and which is being put right for the future, there is an
overwhelming case for government to underwrite the Maxwell pension schemes.
Colin Cornwall,
chairman,
MGN Pension Trustees,
10 Snow Hill,
London,
EC1A 2AL
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6722 Management Investment, Open-End.
    P6371 Pension, Health, and Welfare Funds.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 18
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT932-4220</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DFJB6ADFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930610
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Economic Viewpoint: Why German costs now look so high
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SAMUEL BRITTAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A spectre is beginning to haunt the European Community, that of
Euro-competitiveness - or rather the lack of it. It is invoked by
protectionists in industries such as steel, coal and textiles, who ask how
western European industry can compete - to use the fashionable exaggeration
 -with Czech workers on a 10th of the EC wage, or south-east Asian workers
on a 40th. It is used as an argument against fuel taxes or other
anti-pollution measures. The threat of 'Europe becoming uncompetitive' is
even used in support of good causes such as flexible working hours, or when
arguing against social chapter-type proposals which would raise labour
costs.
It is also likely that, for want of anything else, Euro-competitiveness will
be the rabbit that the European Commission president, Jacques Delors, will
pull out of the hat when he presents his own document on recession and
unemployment to EC leaders at the Copenhagen summit. For it will appeal both
to the protectionists and to the more superficial free market advocates. It
will also give the Community a ragged flag around which to rally when trying
to act tough in trade matters with the US or ex-communist countries. Yet it
is mostly a muddle.
There is a vague sense in which western Europe is losing relative position,
and China and the other Asian developing countries are catching up -
although that is not the same thing as lack of competitiveness. The average
growth rate of the EC since 1975 has been about 2 per cent a year and that
of the US a shade higher. On the other hand, Asian countries have been
growing as a group by 6 to 7 per cent a year.
The more successful developing countries will thus account, if they maintain
their momentum, for a larger part of world output, relative to the older
industrial countries. This is a natural and desirable catching-up process. A
small group of North Atlantic countries cannot hope to stay in the lead
forever.
How about another conventional, if disputable, index of competitiveness, the
current balance of payments? In the EC as a whole, a deficit has emerged
equivalent to just under 1 per cent of its combined GDP with the rest of the
world, and its financing causes no trouble.
If there is a problem of uncompetitiveness in the mundane sense of a pattern
of costs and exchange rates so high as to price products out of world
markets, it is almost exclusively a German one.
There have been many French business complaints about losing competitiveness
to Italy, Spain and the UK as a result of recent devaluations. This,
however, has been made up by the improvement of competitiveness against
Germany which started in 1988 and has been increasing in momentum.
The measurement of the real exchange rate is difficult and controversial.
But IMF indices of normalised unit labour costs, adjusted for exchange rate
variation, suggest France is just as competitive as it was two years ago -
although slightly less than one year ago - and has retained most of the
gains of the late 1980s.
Germany, on the other hand, suffered an explosive increase in unit labour
costs after unification. The adjoining chart may give an exaggerated
impression because of the inclusion of rapidly rising east German wages
unconnected with productivity gains. That surely, however, is part of
Germany's problem.
If the German authorities did not care about inflation, cutting interest
rates sharply and letting the D-Mark fall would be a way of stimulating the
economy in a short-term and superficial way. It would remove one source of
tension with its neighbours by allowing European interest rates to fall, but
probably gain another by giving rise to complaints of competitive
depreciation.
Of course, the Bundesbank has no desire for a D-Mark depreciation - a high
real exchange rate helps to damp down German inflationary pressures.
Nevertheless, the chart does make the case for a French depreciation against
the D-Mark, on which so many market scribes were recently keen, seem
ludicrous. Indeed a bigger, if slightly longer-term, problem is the risk of
the D-Mark taking an undesired drop. The fact that George Soros has come
independently to the same conclusion does not make it true. But it is at
least a straw in the wind.
Even with the present policy of small and stately cuts in German interest
rates, there is clear downside risk on the D-Mark. But France and Germany's
smaller neighbours have inflation rates up to 2 per cent less than
Germany's, which makes their own real interest rates correspondingly higher
and more painful at a time of general recession.
Maybe the increase in German costs can be treated as once and for all, and
the D-Mark can be kept high on the basis of a tough monetary policy
offsetting a big budget deficit and swollen internal costs. Yet this is no
basis for a stable European Monetary System. A comparison can be made with
the strong dollar of President Reagan's early years, when Fed tight money
was offsetting a large US budget deficit. The combination would have been no
basis for a worldwide monetary system.
Ideally, France should take over the role of anchor country from Germany.
Taking over the anchor role is not something that can be done overnight by
firing a gun from the Elysee Palace. The Banque de France has got away in
recent weeks with periods when very short-term interest rates have been a
tiny fraction below Germany's. But the tie-up with German rates is still
close.
What could happen in the period ahead is a gradual differential fall in the
interest rates of the countries which form the hard core of the exchange
rate mechanism. In other words, a sizeable interest rate differential could
eventually develop against Germany, as French and other interest rates fall
slightly faster. The interest rate gap would be the insurance premium
Germany would have to pay to offset the risks of a D-Mark depreciation.
This would be a sharp break with the image that people have formed of the
German economy and currency. But stranger and sharper breaks have occurred
in the past.
Similar charts show that Japan has also had a sharp rise in its real
exchange rate. In the past, Japan has been better than other countries at
reversing such movements through a mixture of productivity gains and wage
moderation. Its ability to do so is now more open to question, and the
American campaign for a higher yen is singularly ill-advised. The Bank of
Japan could, however, help to reverse at least part of the yen appreciation
by still easier and cheaper money, and not assume that present 3.3 per cent
short-term interest rates are necessarily rock bottom.
The country that has gained the greatest competitive advantage is
undoubtedly the UK. On an IMF unit labour cost basis, costs corrected for
exchange rates are 15 to 20 per cent below what they were before departure
from the ERM, and about 10 per cent lower than when the British government
was shadowing the D-Mark in the winter of 1987-88. It is hard work
persuading continental friends that this depreciation was forced on the
government.
Any further depreciation of sterling - whether intentional as the Red/Black
coalition of critics on the government's left and right would like, or as a
by-product of attempts to push recovery faster - would lead to accusations
of competitive devaluation in earnest and could even put the single market
at risk. The ERM may have had its fault lines, but these are nothing
compared with the defects of unbridled currency nationalism.
</TEXT>
