<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Letter: Labour principles still relevant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr NORMAN WILLIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, The article by Frances Williams, 'Soft bark and not much of a bite'
(June 2), betrayed a lack of perspective regarding the influence and role of
the International Labour Organisation and gave an unbalanced account of its
position and achievements. The ILO is not alone in having to come to terms
with the social, economic and political debris left by the communist regimes
in central and eastern Europe. But it is worth noting that most of the
countries of the region are using ILO conventions as the basis for the
development of labour legislation, putting their trust in tripartite
consultation and reaffirming commitment to freedom of association in
tackling vast economic problems.
The ILO alone provides comprehensive accounts of the extent of bonded and
child labour, poverty, unemployment, and risks to safety and health round
the world which must be the starting point for efforts to eradicate those
evils. It alone exposes repressive governments to detailed public scrutiny
and cross-questioning about violations of conventions protecting human
rights which it authoritatively identifies. From our experience, I know ILO
criticisms and condemnations have had some impact even on the UK government,
despite a shameless offensive of misrepresentation and disparagement of the
organisation on those occasions.
Recollection of the catastrophic experience of social breakdown and
injustice which led to two wars, to the foundation of the ILO and inspired
its development after 1944 seems to be unfashionable now. However,
increasingly we see that reputable economic commentators are joining the ILO
in exposing the abject failure in economic, as well as social terms, of the
Thatcher experiment to show that the values of solidarity, justice,
consultation and commitment to gradual social improvement are central to
long-term economic success and to peace.
There may be just criticism of the ILO for buying uncritically so much of
the neo-liberal message and for failing to give a lead in fighting mass
unemployment. That, too, in my view, arises from pursuit of a passing
fashion; it does not bring any discredit to the principles on which the ILO
was founded. They are still relevant and the international community will
return to them.
Norman Willis,
general secretary,
Trades Union Congress,
Great Russell Street,
London WC1B 3LS
</TEXT>
