<PROFILE>_AN-DFJB6ADAFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930610
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Arts: The Stuttgart Ballet
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLEMENT CRISP
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Stuttgart Ballet meant a great deal to Sir Kenneth MacMillan. His friend
and contemporary, John Cranko, directed the troupe. Cranko it was who
invited MacMillan to stage The Song of the Earth when, in 1965, Covent
Garden had thrown its hands up in horror at the idea of a ballet using
Mahler's symphony. Subsequently, Macmillan was to create other major works
on the Stuttgart dancers, responding to such artists as Marcia Haydee,
Birgit Keil, Richard Cragun - My Brother, My Sisters, one of his finest
portraits of the ensemble - and his Requiem was made for Stuttgart in 1977
as a memorial to John Cranko.
It is fitting, then, that Peter Wright should have invited the Stuttgart
Ballet to give two commemorative performances in Birmingham this week, in
tribute to MacMillan. And very properly the repertory comprised Song of the
Earth and Requiem. On Tuesday night I found Song of the Earth an inevitable
and heart-searching journey, as ever in the Stuttgart interpretation. The
central figure of The Woman is safe with Annie Mayet. Her dancing had the
dignity in grief, and the integrity of utterance, which are central facts of
the ballet itself, and her reading was beautiful because without
affectation: movement as essence of experience.
I thought Benito Marcelino a powerful Messenger; Wolfgang Stollwitzer rose
to the great moments of the Man's role, though it is a part which can
benefit from a denser physical presence. Musically, the performance by the
Royal Ballet Sinfonietta under Davor Krnjak was distinguished - texture
clear; sonorities pungent - and Peter Jeffes' tenor blazed grandly in his
three songs.
About Requiem I had reservations. From the first, the ensemble showed that
directness of response to MacMillan's daring imagery - fists raised to
Heaven; mouths agape - which is essential if the piece is to convince us.
Both Richard Cragun and Birgit Keil, in the roles they created, maintain
that purity of intention (no mannerisms; not one beatific or mock-anguished
spasm) which is vital the the sense of the choreography. But Susanne Hanke
performed the Sanctus as if opening a charity bazaar, and Marcia Haydee -
paying her own tribute to MacMillan by returning to the Pie Jesu that he
made for her - seemed all too consciously innocent. (The choreography was
inspired by MacMillan's very young daughter dancing to this same music, and
Haydee's original performance was transparent.) And though we are taught
that diamonds are forever, this is not part of the text of the Mass, and I
find the glitter of ear-studs worn by the leading women less than convincing
as theology or emotion.
The lighting of the set was far from happy. In the first production, the
action seemed bathed in a luminosity which filled translucent columns and
spilled over the stage and was absorbed into the dance itself. On Tuesday
night, the light was misty, dull, and the set glum. The ballet suffered.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7922 Theatrical Producers and Services.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 17
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT932-4226</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DFJB6AC9FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930610
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Arts: Artistic life of Athens transformed - Max Loppert
confirms his initial impression of the Megaron Mousikis Athenon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAX LOPPERT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Athens has acquired for itself one of the great arts centres of Europe: of
this there can now be not the smallest doubt. The Megaron Mousikis Athenon,
a superbly finished building which sets its two differently-sized
performance halls amidst airily handsome white-marble foyers, has
transformed the artistic life of the city. Everyone you meet says so, in
tones of passionate conviction characteristic of the born-again believer.
I first visited the Megaron in May last year, some months after the centre
had been inaugurated. An invitation to make a return tour of inspection last
week revealed previously missing finishing touches now in place. The
magnificent organ in the Friends' Hall (the 2,000-seater) will shortly be in
action. Beautifully planted gardens have been opened for concert-interval
strolling. A well-ordered buffet restaurant in the basement operates for
post-performance dining.
Every detail - apart, perhaps, from the slight shortage of leg-room in
upper-tier seating - seems precise in purpose, exactly executed,
un-ostentatiously right. The practicability of the Megaron, which was
designed to place up-to-date technology at the service of all the various
purposes for which the building was intended, is a remarkable achievement -
and, in the light of the various impracticable opera theatres and
concert-halls that have recently been unveiled elsewhere in Europe, one
rather too obviously exceptional.
Its flexibility was fully demonstrated during my two-day sojourn. On my
first morning the Friends' Hall was a conference venue for the presentation
of the annual Onassis Awards (worth Dollars 100,000, and given this year to,
among others, Vaclav Havel and Peter Brook). That evening it was a
music-theatre space, with an orchestra pit opened out front-of-platform, for
the semi-staging of a Gluck opera. The next evening the side-boxes of
additional seating had been slid back into position, the pit was closed and
on stage the full Berlin Philharmonic Orchestra under Claudio Abbado was
assembled for a concert of Schubert and Mahler symphonies.
Two thematic strands dominate seasonal programme-building at the Megaron:
these two successive events exemplified them. A 'Great Orchestras of the
World' series is the first strand. The Berlin Philharmonic concert was its
concluding and, indeed, culminating item: this is the first of the world's
super-elite orchestras to appear in the Megaron, and its playing of the
Mahler Fifth Symphony drove the Athens public into ecstasies.
These were easy enough to understand. In a hall of such marvellously
well-balanced, responsive acoustics, where the full range of Mahler scoring
device is permitted to 'sound' with ideal clarity and exactitude of
perspective, the Berlin orchestral ensemble was displayed in all its glory.
A nit-picker might sense, as I did, that in middle age Abbado has loosened
his grip on Mahlerian symphonic drama - memories of LSO Mahler performances
suggest, perhaps unfairly, that he now tends to dull its cutting edge of
irony, soften its lyrical contours, make less jagged its heights and depths.
But under his musical directorship the great qualities of an orchestra for
so long thought of as 'Karajan's band' are certainly not lost: the Athens
concert hall experience proved as much.
The second seasonal strand is the cyclic representation of a figure from
Greek mythology - last year Electra, this year Helen, next year Medea - by
means of operas, plays, symposia, lectures and other related events.
Strauss's Aegyptische Helena (with Anna Tomowa-Sintow) had a full-scale
staging last month; a brand-new Greek opera entitled The Return of Helen and
the Euripides play Helen are due in the next few weeks.
Alongside these, the choice of Gluck's Iphigenie en Tauride (in which Helen
figures only tangentially, as the offstage provoker of the various tragedies
visited on the house of Agamemnon) rather than the admittedly less
well-known Paride ed Elena (in which Helen is the heroine) proved distinctly
odd. Nevertheless, since the performance itself was a triumph of restrained
yet passionate Gluck interpretation, and had clearly an overwhelming effect
on the huge audience, excuses for its addition to the Helen cycle were in
the end unnecessary.
Ellen Shade (Iphigenia), Francois le Roux (Orestes), and Donald Kaasch
(Pylades) led the eloquently expressive cast; the Austrian Concentus Vocalis
choir and the English Chamber Orchestra were conducted by Marc Soustrot.
There was no scenery to speak of. The chorus stood in serried ranks, the
singers moved on and off a central dais, changes of lighting played on the
organ in the background. One of the supreme examples of opera-as-drama
economy was rendered with extraordinary accuracy, tact, directness and
emotional force. As always happens in successful operatic accounts of this
sort, one came away brooding about the amount of fuss, tat and wasted effort
that goes into the average modern opera production.
Berlin Philharmonic tour sponsored by Deutsche Bank AG
</TEXT>
<XX>
