<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Technology: A quick-fix telecoms solution - DHL is using
microwave frequencies in Moscow to bypass the city's overloaded exchanges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Not many western companies operating in Moscow have reason to be grateful to
the KGB. But when the courier firm DHL set up its new Moscow telephone link
this month, it marked not only an innovation in Russian telephone
technology, but also a considerable coup in terms of post-cold war
co-operation.
What makes DHL's telephone system unusual - and the co-operation of the KGB
necessary - is its use of microwave technology.
A radio transmission system popular in military communications, microwaves
have been used in telephone systems since the end of the 1980s, either to
circumvent existing cable or copper networks, or to provide extensions to
them.
But though now commonplace in the west, they have been slow to appear in
eastern Europe, where microwave frequencies have been controlled by the
local military and the emerging western-style telecommunications
infrastructure has focused on satellite, cellular radio and fibre-optic
systems.
'This is the first time microwave has been used in Russia,' says Kevin
Edmond, director of Hermes telecommunications company which installed the
link.
Hermes hopes microwave will provide a viable telecommunications alternative
for other businesses in eastern Europe.
Judging from DHL's story, the system does seem to have some advantages of
speed and flexibility, particularly for smaller businesses which want to use
satellite services.
In common with many companies operating in eastern Europe, DHL had arrived
in Moscow to find a familiar saga of telecommunication woes.
Although it had originally asked the local telephone authorities to supply
30 lines on one number, it had received five lines, each on different
numbers - resulting in engaged telephones and frustrated customers.
Since the local exchange was already heavily overloaded, there was little
hope of gaining any extra lines through the local system.
'There is such a shortage, they said they could only give us new lines when
another user died,' explains Steve Csikai, DHL's IT manager.
Since establishing its own satellite link would have been extremely
expensive, DHL began to explore ways of using those run by Comstar, a joint
venture between the British company GPT and Moscow Telecommunications
Network (MGTS), through the existing UK-built System X exchange in Moscow.
But because DHL's offices were located 38km from the exchange, linking into
this presented a problem - either they would have to use the local network,
which would place them at the mercy of the Russian telephone system again,
or lay a new fibre-optic cable which would be a lengthy process.
'Putting wires across Moscow means digging up roads, which all takes a lot
of time - in our case at least six months,' says Csikai. At that point,
Hermes suggested a microwave link, which was potentially quicker and
cheaper, representing a total investment of around Dollars 150,000 (Pounds
97,400).
Establishing the link required extensive negotiation with the local security
services and considerable engineering innovation. To ensure a clear
transmission path between DHL's low-lying offices and the Comstar exchange,
an antenna had to be suspended from a nearby tower block, surrounded by
metal cages and locked steel doors to guard against theft.
But a month after the operation started DHL received the 40 new lines,
offering international phone calls at a cost ranging from Dollars 1 to
Dollars 5 a minute.
As other telecommunications operators point out, the system still has
drawbacks, especially for larger businesses.
Compared with optical fibre, microwave's capacity is relatively limited  -
the DHL link, for example, carries 4 channels of 2 megabits - or the
potential equivalent of 120 lines. The optical fibre cables being laid by
Comstar carry 32 optical fibres, each carrying 34 megabits, soon to be
upgraded to 155 megabits, representing the potential for thousands of lines.
Another problem lies in transmission. Because laser-thin signals are beamed
between stations which have to be in line of sight, the receivers cannot be
more than a horizon apart - usually about 40km.
Although this distance can be extended by relay stations, transmission can
be affected by obstructions - severe weather conditions for example, can
cause delays - and if any new buildings are constructed in the pathway, the
signal must be re-routed.
'Microwave is a quick-fix solution,' says Ken Norman, project director of
Comstar, who insists that the real future for telecommunications in Russia
lies with optical fibre systems. Comstar, for example, has already laid
1,060km of optical fibre cable across Moscow.
Nevertheless, DHL insists that as far as its own telecommunications needs
are concerned, the link is effective. Furthermore, for a courier company
which relies on advertising a well-known number, the system has one big
advantage - if it moves premises, it will be able to take its telephone
number without needing to lay more cable.
'In the end our customers don't care what the 'phone system is, just so long
as they just can rely on getting through,' says Csikai.
</TEXT>
