<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Management (Marketing and Advertising): When the bubbles go
flat - France's champagne houses have been forced to reduce prices in an
attempt to maintain sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The streets of Epernay in eastern France were last week filled with angry
champagne workers protesting against proposed job losses at some of France's
finest champagne houses.
The redundancies are the culmination of three intensely difficult years
which have seen the champagne industry hit by falling sales, rising raw
material prices and, since September, by the impact of the strong franc on
exports. Stocks have risen to record levels. Some small companies have
serious cashflow problems.
The champagne houses now face the challenge of trying to regenerate sales
without jeopardising the exclusive image of their product.
To some degree the industry's difficulties are a hangover of its success in
the 1980s. Champagne sales soared from 147m bottles in 1982 to 249m in 1989.
The price of champagne, and of the grapes used to make it, rose accordingly.
The grape price peaked in 1990 (at FFr32.00 per kilo against FFr19.00 in
1982) the same year that sales started to decline.
The producers retaliated by raising their prices just as they had in the
1980s. But the market could no longer absorb the increases. Champagne sales
fell to 232m bottles in 1990 and fell again as the recession deepened to
214m in 1991 and 1992.
The conventional marketing response to such a decline in demand would be to
try to boost sales through advertising.
LVMH tried this last Christmas by running a campaign in France for Moet, its
flagship brand. Taittinger also advertised in France. But these campaigns
failed to stop the decline in sales as the industry's problems are too
complex for advertising to offer more than a partial solution.
Although the market appeared to stabilise last year, the total of 214m
bottles disguises a rapid rise in sales of low-quality petits champagnes
dumped by smaller cash-strapped producers and which retail for as little as
FFr35.00 (Pounds 4.20) a bottle in France.
These petits champagnes have not only eroded the position of higher-quality
brands, but also imposed intense pressure on prices and profitability across
the market.
Some large houses have retaliated by launching their own petits champagnes.
Taittinger last year re-introduced Irroy, a product that dates back to the
1860s but has been 'remaindered' for many years. Irroy now sells for 25 per
cent less than the Taittinger brand. The relaunch has been so successful
that Taittinger has developed a new, cheap champagne, Saint-Evremond, which
reaches the shops this month.
'There have always been secondary champagnes, just as there are second and
third pressings of Bordeaux,' said Philippe Court, chief executive of
Taittinger. 'The secondary brands come out at certain times and then
disappear. We decided the time was right to bring them out again.'
But the industry's chief response to the crisis has been to cut prices. In
past recessions the champagne producers have been able to avoid this because
they could shelter behind high inflation.
The current downturn, however, has taken place at a time of low inflation in
most leading champagne markets. The leading houses have this time held
prices for as long as possible, for fear that discounting lower prices would
intensify the pressure on their profits and, in the long term, jeopardise
their product's prestigious reputation.
Some of the grandest houses, notably Bollinger, have held prices. 'Bollinger
is at the very top of the market,' says Christian Bizot, chairman. 'We would
never do anything that might devalue it.' Others have bowed to market
pressure.
'Taittinger has reduced prices along with most of the other houses,' says
Court. 'We might not like it, but we had no choice.'
Even price cutting has been problematic. The franc's strength against the
UK, Spanish and Italian currencies since last autumn's ERM crisis has not
only depressed the repatriated profits from the champagne sold in those
countries, but raised the risk of parallel imports coming into France and
Germany, where currencies are stronger.
LVMH, after struggling for months to maintain prices, announced in February
it was 'temporarily' cutting the wholesale price of Moet and Mercier by 10
per cent in France, Germany and Switzerland. However it was also forced to
raise the price of those brands by 5 per cent in the UK, Italy and Spain to
prevent parallel imports.
These changes are now filtering through to the shops. LVMH says it is still
too soon to assess their effect on sales. But the group faces the additional
problem of how its retail customers will react to reductions in wholesale
pricing. LVMH might finish in the unenviable position of having reduced its
margins through price cutting, without deriving any benefit from higher
sales.
That said, there are some positive signs for the industry. The petits
champagnes may have depressed prices, but the availability of so much cheap
product has at least prevented sparkling wines from taking market share from
champagne.
Meanwhile, sales are starting to improve in the US, as the economy emerges
from recession. This augurs well, not only for that market, but also for
champagne's prospects in other countries as their economic problems ease.
'It's important to remember that the level of champagne sales last year, at
214m bottles, was significantly higher than the last low of 147m in 1982,'
says Sylvain Massot, European drinks analyst at Morgan Stanley. 'This
suggests that champagne's success in the 1980s wasn't a temporary phenomenon
and that the product has substantial underlying strengths.'
Some champagne houses are less optimistic. One issue is that the continuing
trend towards low inflation poses serious problems for pricing in the
future. They also fear that the proliferation of petits champagnes could
cause long-term damage to the industry's image.
Bollinger is mooting plans for the grand houses to lobby for greater
differentiation (in terms of labelling and product classification) between
grands champagnes and cheap bubbly.
'It's ridiculous to expect Bollinger to carry the same name as something
selling for FFr36.00,' says Bizot.
'A grand champagne is recognised as one of the world's great products and,
whatever happens, we must make sure that it stays that way.'
