<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Group 4 concerned about London contract
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FRESH COMPLICATIONS over the legal rights of public employees transferring
to the private sector may arise when the government puts London's prison
escort services out to tender soon.
Group 4 - the private security company which is seeking the contract and has
been shortlisted to manage Strangeways prison, Manchester - might withdraw
from the bidding if it is forced to operate on public-sector rates.
In April Group 4 started operating Britain's first privately managed prison
escort service - in the east Midlands, Yorkshire and Humberside  - using
newly recruited staff. It is a leading contender for the Pounds 25m-a-year
contract for escorting prisoners in the London area.
But Group 4 managers have written to the government pointing out that unlike
other police forces, the Metropolitan Police has its own dedicated team of
officers working exclusively on prison escort duties. Mr Jim Harrower, Group
4 chief executive, said yesterday the company was concerned that this might
mean the 1981 Transfer of Undertakings (Protection of Employment)
Regulations (Tupe) might apply. These guarantee public-sector employees
transferred to private companies maintenance of pay and conditions.
'If the London court escort service had to operate on police pay rates and
conditions it would radically alter our attitude to the contract,' said Mr
Harrower. 'We have expressed concern to the government.'
Group 4 has received formal notification from the Prison Service Agency that
it has been shortlisted from among seven bidders to manage the rebuilt
Strangeways.
It already manages Wolds remand prison, Humberside. 'But we do not want to
just be involved in prison management,' said Mr Harrower. 'Even though most
prisons will remain under public-sector management we want to become an
alternative prison authority, providing a complete range of training,
education and other services.'
He said the company would bid to run the new Doncaster prison, which will
follow Strangeways as the next candidate for market testing.
The Doncaster contract has particular attractions for Group 4, as it is in
the same region as Wolds and the company's current prison escort contract,
opening the possibility of one private-sector company providing all penal
services in an area.
</TEXT>
