<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Teachers oppose training proposal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN PATTEN, the education secretary, yesterday added fuel to his
confrontation with teachers' unions by announcing plans to allow
non-graduates to teach in primary schools.
The proposal, which is intended to take effect from September 1994, met with
a furious response from teachers and head teachers on the day that the
controversial national curriculum tests on Shakespeare for 14-year-olds were
widely boycotted.
One-year courses would be introduced for teaching children up to the age of
seven. These would be open to mature students without degrees, provided they
had experience of dealing with children, and had sufficient academic
qualifications to gain entry to higher education.
Mr Patten also intends to diversify entrance to the teaching profession with
a new three-year BEd course which would qualify students to teach all six
subjects of the national curriculum for primary schools.
Mr David Hart, general secretary of the National Association of Head
Teachers said he strongly opposed the move away from graduate entry.
Mr Nigel de Gruchy, general secretary of the National Association of
Schoolmasters/Union of Women Teachers, said the union was considering a
boycott of the new training arrangements. He said: 'There's certainly no
requirement in our contracts to train people from scratch.'
Mr Doug McAvoy, general secretary of the National Union of Teachers, said:
'The government's plan is an attack on the all-graduate agreed by Margaret
Thatcher in 1974. Lady Thatcher must be turning in her ermine.'
Mrs Ann Taylor, shadow education secretary, described the plan as 'one of
the barmiest government schemes to date'.
</TEXT>
