<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Recession reduces regional divide
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SOCIAL CHANGES in the 1980s and the effects of the recession are challenging
traditional images of the UK's north-south divide, Regional Trends, the
annual government statistical publication, shows today.
Ms Alison Holding, associate editor, said this year's edition showed the
recession had proved 'quite a leveller'.
By the start of this year unemployment in the south-east, at 10.5 per cent,
was higher than in Scotland, Wales or the east Midlands.
Families in the south-east outside London are still most likely to own their
own homes - 75 per cent do so, compared with a national average of 68 per
cent - but other regions have caught up. Owner-occupation in the north grew
from 48 per cent to 61 per cent between 1981 and 1991.
The report shows a relatively even spread of professional and managerial
employment across the country.
While the south-east comes first with 8.1 per cent of its population being
professionals and another 30.7 per cent of its male working population in
managerial occupations, East Anglia and the south-west both have 6.5 per
cent professionals and about 27 per cent in managerial work.
Regional Trends 28, 1993. HMSO. Pounds 26.
</TEXT>
