<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Unions call for role in forum
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TRADE union movement made a plea yesterday for greater recognition of
the role it can play in developing a long-term strategy to boost industrial
competitiveness.
In evidence to the Commons trade and industry committee the Trades Union
Congress said that since the demise of the National Economic Development
Office last year there had been no national forum to discuss industrial
competitiveness. The TUC said: 'For the government to talk only to employers
is to narrow the focus of debate, and is more likely than not to lead to the
kind of corporatism they seek to avoid.'
Mr Roger Lyons, general secretary of the MSF technical union, told MPs that
'the most successful companies listen to their employees. But the Department
of Trade and Industry does not seem to want that information'.
The committee, investigating the competitiveness of UK manufacturing, also
heard evidence from the Engineering Employers' Federation.
Illustrating the degree of common ground between unions and employers on the
need for a long-term industrial strategy, Mr Neil Johnson, the federation's
director-general, said the government should take a 30-to-40-year view of
the direction of industry and technology.
</TEXT>
