<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Ban urged on sale of non-approved modems
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ELECTRONICS manufacturers in the UK are urging the government to declare
illegal the sale of computer communications equipment that has not been
approved for connection to the public switched network.
They are angry that US and Asian companies are able to undercut their prices
by supplying equipment that has not been subjected to or passed the
extensive tests required by the BATB, the UK telecommun-ications equipment
watchdog.
It is not, at present, illegal to sell non-approved data communications
equipment although it is against the law to attach it to the public
telephone network.
An industry lobby, the Modem Approvals Group, has been established which
next Wednesday will launch a campaign at the Commons to spread awareness of
the need to establish a 'level playing field' for manufacturers prepared to
comply with the regulations.
Modems are pieces of electronic equipment which convert computer data into
signals which can be transmitted down a telephone line. They are an
essential component in the construction of computer networks which
represents one of the fastest growing areas of the information technology
business and a potential source of significant revenues to UK suppliers.
Mr Joe Korner, a marketing executive with the UK manufacturer Dataflex
Design which has been in the forefront of the campaign, said that 'grey'
importers could sell for about Pounds 100, a modem that Dataflex priced at
Pounds 199.
The modem market is worth some Dollars 310m in the UK at present, according
to the marketing consultancy Dataquest, equivalent to 340,000 units. Between
20 per cent and 40 per cent of the total is thought to be accounted for by
grey imports.
Members of the Modem Approvals Group include Dataflex, Cray
Communications,Racal, Motorola Codex, British Telecom and Psion Datacom.
The group has already brought the issue to the attention of the Department
of Trade and Industry and to Oftel.
Mr Barry Gilder, marketing director of Cray Communications, said there was a
question of safety but the real issue was establishing fair trading
conditions for manufacturers.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
