<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Minister digs in on terror insurance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government yesterday refused to back down from its plans to increase
premiums charged for terrorism insurance, in spite of protests from the
City, business organisations and insurers.
Mr Neil Hamilton, the minister for corporate affairs, said 'there was no
option' but to go ahead with the rate increases. Last month Pool Re, the
government-backed reinsurance company, announced rises that would come into
effect for all policies sold after July 1.
Owners of the largest properties in areas most vulnerable to terrorist
attack face increases of more than 300 per cent in premium rates. Mr Bernard
Harty, the chamberlain of the Corporation of London, which manages about a
third of properties in the City, said the increase would 'add to cost at a
time of recession'.
However, Mr Hamilton said that the insurance represented 'good value for
money'.
A building in central London valued at Pounds 100m would pay Pounds 144,000
for terrorism insurance, which he said was a relatively small amount
compared to rental and other costs. Businesses in some areas will benefit
from rate reductions, he added.
Insurers fear that the rate rises could persuade many businesses to run the
risk of not carrying insurance protection, and undermine the effectiveness
of the Pool Re scheme. This was agreed last year after insurers decided to
withdraw terrorism cover from standard commercial policies following
bombings in the City.
Matters have been complicated by the Bishopsgate bomb this year which
exhausted funds collected to date by Pool Re. Increasingly, business appears
to favour the addition of a compulsory levy to all insurance policies,
spreading terrorism cover costs more widely across the country.
Mr Harty said organisations attending a meeting at the Department of Trade
and Industry yesterday were looking into alternative schemes that they hoped
to present to Mr Hamilton before the end of the year.
</TEXT>
