<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Access to Cyprus sought for SFO
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK and JOHN MURRAY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is negotiating with the authorities in northern Cyprus in an
attempt to win access to the island for the Serious Fraud Office regarding
its investigation of Mr Asil Nadir, the fugitive businessman and former head
of Polly Peck International.
It hopes the SFO will be able to gain informal access to information and
individuals in the region.
Formal diplomatic requests for co-operation with the authorities have
failed.
The discussions form continued pressure by the British authorities on the
self-proclaimed Turkish republic of northern Cyprus, under the threat of
trade or other sanctions.
Ms Lorna Harris, the SFO lawyer handling the Nadir case, last night returned
to London after three days of what the British Embassy in Ankara called
'constructive discussions' relating to Mr Nadir's abscondment. She met a
range of government officials including those in the Ministry of Justice.
Mr Colin Jennings, British deputy high commissioner for Cyprus, confirmed
yesterday that he had met Mr Rauf Denktash, the president of northern
Cyprus, and Mr Dervish Eroglu, the prime minister, on Monday.
He said British High Commission representatives had met officials in
northern Cyprus about six times since Mr Nadir jumped bail last month.
The renewed pressure comes in advance of a preparatory hearing in the High
Court to consider the case on June 15.
</TEXT>
