<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Law Society in the dock over its regulatory role: Robert
Rice on a case that could have serious implications for SROs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE High Court will today begin hearing a case brought by a 77-year-old
woman against the Law Society, the solicitors' professional body, which
could have important implications for all self-regulating organisations.
Miss Peggy Wood is suing the society for its alleged failure to investigate
properly her complaints against her former solicitors after she lost her
home and development land.
If she wins, the case could set a precedent by deciding that regulatory
bodies owe a duty of care to the public in investigating complaints and that
they must pay damages to those who suffer loss as a result of their failure
to uphold that duty.
The society admits it was wrong to dismiss her initial complaint but denies
that it owes a duty of care to anyone who loses because of its failure to
investigate properly.
On Tuesday the High Court ruled that Miss Wood, who had her legal aid
withdrawn last November and who lives on income support and so cannot afford
a barrister, could be assisted by a 'friend', Mr Ole Hanson, a solicitor and
journalist. Because Miss Wood is in poor health and partially deaf Mr Hanson
is to be allowed to address the court on her behalf. Normally 'friends' are
restricted to taking notes and giving advice.
The court ruled that because the case raised issues of public importance a
barrister should be briefed by the Official Solicitor as amicus curiae to
assist the court with the legal issues raised by her claim.
Miss Wood was also given permission to amend her claim against the society
to allege conspiracy to injure her cause by the leaking of confidential
legal aid information.
Her complaint against her former solicitors, Hubbard &amp; Co of Chichester,
West Sussex, dates back to 1973 when, left without any income, she consulted
Mrs Sylvia Hubbard about obtaining four loans totalling Pounds 10,000
secured against her home.
When she was unable to repay the loans the firm acted against her on behalf
of the lenders. The main lender, Mobile Homes, was 50 per cent owned by Mrs
Hubbard's husband, Joseph, then also a partner in the firm.
Miss Wood was evicted and her house sold leaving her with just Pounds 1,400
after all her debts had been paid. Following modernisation, the house and
another house built on the land were resold for almost Pounds 200,000.
Miss Wood complained to the society of conflict of interest and professional
misconduct by Hubbards. The society initially refused to investigate but
later issued a reprimand. In 1987 she accepted Pounds 2,500, which had been
paid into court, in settlement of her claim for negligence and breach of
duty against the firm.
The hearing is expected to last two weeks.
</TEXT>
