<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / South-west hit by defence cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, Wales and West Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DEFENCE CUTS are having a more damaging impact on the south-west of England
than anywhere else in the UK and are likely to lead to a slower recovery
from the recession, says a survey of 331 companies in the region.
Half of the companies - representing nearly a third of the region's gross
domestic product - said they received some defence-related orders.
Twenty-eight per cent said that defence cuts had been significant in
limiting their performance.
The survey, published yesterday, was produced jointly by the Confederation
of British Industry south-western region, accountants Coopers &amp; Lybrand and
the University of the West of England.
In the defence supply chain, over a third of the businesses that supplied
goods and services to the defence industry said they needed aid for
investment and to develop new markets.
Mr Chris Curtis, the CBI's regional director, called for assistance from the
European regional development fund. 'The impact of defence cuts in the
south-west is akin to the effect on south Wales of the rundown of the coal
and steel industries,' he said.
Mr Chris Tillett, associate director of Coopers &amp; Lybrand, said: 'It came as
no surprise that defence cuts were a key concern to south-west business.
What is striking, though, was the spread and depth of exposure of south-west
firms, and the scale of the knock-on impact.'
Mr Derek Braddon, the university's research director in defence economics,
said the survey confirmed the worst fears about the scale of job losses and
economic shockwaves caused by defence cuts. Already, about 25,000 jobs in
the region had been lost in consequence. A forecast two years ago that
40,000 jobs would go by the end of the decade was probably now an
underestimate.
He said that if Devonport dockyard at Plymouth lost a pending
nuclear-submarine refitting contract to Rosyth in Scotland, it would be 'a
very big disaster' for the south-west.
Positioned for Recovery? The Future of South West Business. CBI South
Western Region, 8-10 Whiteladies Road, Bristol BS8 1NZ. Pounds 5.
</TEXT>
