<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / George warns against cut in interest rates:
Governor-designate highlights fears on inflation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A STRONG though veiled warning against imminent cuts in interest rates was
delivered last night by Mr Eddie George, who will soon be governor of the
Bank of England.
Mr George, the current deputy governor who steps up to the top job next
month, said in a speech to business leaders in Cambridgeshire that
inflationary pressures were far from dead in spite of Britain's long
recession. While he cast doubt on the notion that further cuts in base rates
would stimulate any significant economic activity, he also signalled that
they might spark rising prices, which would hold back any sustainable
recovery.
Mr George's speech was set in the context of a long-term vision of how he
would like to control monetary policy, an area where the bank at present
advises the Treasury.
However, it was given special resonance by the revelation yesterday that Mr
Norman Lamont, the former chancellor, has secretly pushed the idea of giving
the bank independence to remove politicians from interest-rate judgments.
The governor-designate said there was a worry that 'bringing interest rates
down too far would increase the risk of the re-emergence of inflationary
pressures'. That 'might make lower interest rates difficult to sustain', he
added.
He said Britain had a 'solid platform' for future growth, with unmistakeable
signs of recovery. But he said that with long-term gilt yields relatively
high at 8 per cent, as opposed to base rates of 6 per cent, financial
markets were still unconvinced that Britain had got on top of inflationary
pressures.
Sounding a warning against any further loosening in economic policies, Mr
George said that if people had the confidence that inflation would remain
low, 'then relatively low and relatively stable interest rates will tend to
follow'.
He said it was wrong to opt for lower interest rates and assume that
inflation would also remain low.
In an apparent swipe at those arguing for fresh cuts in base rates, held at
their present levels since January, Mr George said that even if borrowing
costs were lower people would not necessarily spend or borrow more.
That was because of the 'bitter experiences of the late 1980s', in which
many individuals and businesses took advantage of relatively low interest
rates to step up loans and expenditure, only to find themselves in financial
difficulties when the recession began to bite a few years later.
In a further distancing by the bank of any goal to rejoin the European
exchange rate mechanism, Mr George said exchange rate stability, though a
useful goal, could not be achieved at the expense of a 'distortion of
domestic (economic) policy'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
