<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Builders increase housing starts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE REVIVAL in the private housing market is encouraging builders to
increase new housing programmes, official figures published yesterday show.
With housing sales and prices steadily rising, construction activity is
recovering after one of the worst periods for new house building for more
than a decade. Builders are also reporting large price increases for some
development land.
Although figures vary between building societies, the country's largest
mortgage lenders agree that house-sale activity and prices have resumed an
upward trend earlier than many had originally expected. Builders have also
been encouraged by a reduction in the large number of empty homes, which
have inhibited revival in the housing market.
The Department of the Environment said that total housing starts in the
three months to the end of April reached 47,400, a 20 per cent rise from the
previous three months and 6,800 more than in the same period a year earlier.
In April alone, building started on 16,400 homes, compared with 14,000 in
April last year. Builders also completed 14,200 homes for sale during the
month, nearly 2,000 more than a year earlier. Last year private housing
starts reached 121,000 - 100,000 less than the 1988 peak of 221,000.
The latest figures suggest output this year will rise sharply.
</TEXT>
