<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Backbench Tories underwhelmed by
'best leader they have' - Ralph Atkins on how despair among Conservative MPs
betrayed the damage done to the prime minister
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DESPAIR on the Conservative benches
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
and the near absence of the usual waving of order papers for Mr John Major -
yesterday betrayed the injury Mr Norman Lamont's resignation speech had done
to the prime minister's credibility.
Even loyalist MPs admitted Mr Lamont's comments were deeply damaging to Mr
Major. They said the prime minister had failed to respond by creating a
sense of purpose for his government in his own speech. Questions about his
leadership were renewed and reinforced. Rumours about a leadership challenge
later this year were heightened.
Labour MPs's ironic cries of 'more, more,' after Mr Major sat down added to
the sense of disappointment.
Private criticism of Mr Major's leadership style was both scathing and
widespread. 'If he isn't acting as a prime minister soon, he won't be prime
minister at all,' said one Tory.
There was public criticism too, with critical speeches by senior Tories in
the Commons debate.
But, with no challenger to the leadership having yet emerged, there was a
sense of floundering among Conservative MPs. A usually loyal member of the
government said: 'I have got to think about it. We can't make a considered
view. He hasn't shored up his position certainly.'
One minister said: 'We got no other choice'.
Sir Anthony Grant, Conservative MP for Cambridgeshire south west, captured,
perhaps unwittingly, the predicament as he tried to sound supportive: 'He is
certainly the very best leader that we have.'
During Mr Major's Commons speech, as many Tory MPs were sucking fingers in
contemplation - perhaps of the stings inflicted by Mr Lamont - as were
indulging in more traditional attempts to goad the Labour party.
No one expected the prime minister to make a great speech. It is not his
strength. But there was a sense among Conservatives that he could have done
better.
One backbencher suggested that he should have brushed off the jibes from Mr
Lamont, by ignoring them in a statesman-like manner.
But to some Tories the fall-out from Mr Lamont's address was less damaging
than might have been expected.
The prevailing view was that the party had to rally around the government,
rather than create further divisions.
Almost all Tory MPs agreed that the former chancellor's intervention was not
on the same scale as the resignation speech of Sir Geoffrey (now Lord) Howe.
Others criticised the former chancellor's motives.
One junior minister said: 'Lamont is not popular out there. Geoffrey was
respected.'
One moderate MP said: 'Norman Lamont wanted to wound rather than to kill -
though I suppose to want to wound the government these days is bad enough.'
A more careful assessment will precede tonight's meeting of the executive of
the Conservative's 1922 backbench committee, the infamous 'men in grey
suits' who tell prime ministers - frequently bluntly - what the infantry at
Westminster are thinking.
Since the committee is usually ruled by conventions of absolute secrecy,
details of the message which will be sent to Mr Major were unclear last
night. However, at least a few of the 18 executive members were deeply
worried at the Tory party's plummeting morale. 'We are prepared to give him
time, but not indefinitely,' said one.
Another said: 'Morale is definitely low and there is a great deal of anxiety
about but that hasn't manifested itself in a feeling that the government is
about to collapse, a general election is brewing, or that the prime minister
should go.'
But the 1922 executive is also split - with many privately furious at what
they regard as disloyal and injudicious remarks made by colleagues to the
newspapers.
There is disagreement too about tax rises.
Right-wing executive members want none, while the centre-right members want
any public spending cuts balanced by tax increases.
Mr John Townend, chairman of the Tory backbench finance committee, said Mr
Kenneth Clarke, the new chancellor, should, 'forget any idea that he might
have of increasing income tax, particularly the standard rate.'
Adding to the government's embarrasment, Sir Peter Hordern, Tory MP for
Horsham and 1922 executive member, backed Mr Lamont's call for an
independent central bank. 'Monetary policy is not as credible as it might be
if our central bank were to be independent,' he said.
Sir Peter also said that VAT on fuel and power, if needed, should have been
imposed immediately. 'To be blamed without getting any revenue for a year
seems perverse.'
Sir Terence Higgins, Tory MP for Worthing and another member of the 1922
executive, was also critical of the VAT move, saying he thought the
government needed to do more to protect those on incomes just above benefit
levels.
Ironically, last night Mr Lamont's Kingston-upon-Thames constituency was
among those earmarked for re-organisation by the Boundary Commissioners. In
the latest provisional plans the seat is set to be divided between the
Richmond and Barnes constituency and a new one for Kingston and Surbiton.
When the commission started its work there were forecasts that the
Conservatives could benefit by as many as 20 extra seats, but last night's
plans indicate that the figure could be as few as half a dozen - with many
desperately close marginals.
Tory-dominated Essex is set to gain an extra seat but sweeping changes are
planned to the party's flagship marginal at Basildon.
</TEXT>
