<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Buoyant Smith raises his stock -
Smith calls government 'foolishly inept'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A BUOYANT Mr John Smith yesterday acted to defuse recent criticism of his
leadership style by unleashing a withering assault on the government's
credibility and competence.
Exploiting a rare opportunity to grapple with Mr John Major head-to-head in
a full-length Commons debate, the Labour leader hit back at recent internal
rumblings about his 'Horlicks leadership' with a bravura performance which
combined sober economic analysis with good jokes.
Making the most of his opportunity to take aim at an opponent softened up by
former chancellor Norman Lamont's extraordinary resignation statement, Mr
Smith dubbed the hapless prime minister 'the man with the non-Midas touch.'
The government was 'consistently incompetent, hopelessly accident-prone, so
foolishly inept,' he said, listing a panoply of mishaps stretching from
Black Wednesday to last month's 'botched' reshuffle.
It was no wonder we were living in 'a country where the Grand National does
not start and a hotel falls into the sea', he said.
Introducing a motion condemning Mr Major's 'betrayal' of election promises,
Mr Smith started by concentrating on tax increases announced in Mr Lamont's
final Budget, including the extension of VAT to domestic fuel which he said
amounted to a 'staggering' Pounds 17.5bn.
In the 1992 election campaign the prime minister had promised tax cuts year
upon year and said that his party had 'no plans and no need' to extend the
scope of VAT.
Instead it was 'tax increases year on year,' Mr Smith said. 'The stark truth
is that every family in the land will have to foot the cost of this
government's perfidy.' The government was 'prepared to promise anything to
get elected.'
The Labour leader was at pains to emphasise that the less well-off would be
disproportionately affected by some of the Budget changes.
The main difference between putting 1 per cent extra on national insurance
contributions and levying another 1p on income tax was that national
insurance hit the lower paid harder, he said.
Nor had the Conservatives said in their general election campaign that they
would freeze personal income tax allowances in their first post-election
Budget, Mr Smith continued. 'National insurance increases, VAT and frozen
allowances; not quite the double whammy we kept hearing about (in the
election). It has turned out to be the Tories' triple whammy on the British
taxpayer.'
Brushing off a string of angry interventions from the Tory back benches, Mr
Smith argued that what the country was starting to resent was the 'low
ambition' the government had for Britain.
The people of Britain did not want a 'low-wage sweatshop' economy, or 'high
and debilitating' unemployment, or 'confrontation and dogma' in the
classroom.
What they wanted was a government they could trust. No amount of
reshuffling, repackaging and representation could disguise 'the stark
reality of a discredited government presided over by a discredited prime
minister.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
