<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / World Trade News: Kantor outlines US policy towards Japan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IN A broad defence of the emerging controversial US Japan policy, Mr Mickey
Kantor, the US trade representative, said the US could lead the world out of
recession only if Japan reduced its huge and still growing trade surplus.
'It is our responsibility to get our budget deficit under control, invest in
our infrastructure and lead global growth,' he said. 'But we have just got
to do something about the Japanese trade surplus, which creates an
asymmetrical economic situation in the world, costing US jobs.'
In the US-Japan talks set to begin tomorrow, Mr Kantor said he would be
flexible on demands for numerical indicators to measure progress in reducing
that surplus. Other options would also be considered ..'
'We're not telling the Japanese how to reach these goals, how to structure
their economy,' he said. 'We're trying to say we have a problem that needs
to be addressed.'
US concerns were shared by the EC, he said. 'We understand that the
Europeans are currently in the middle of negotiating 20 different sectors
with the Japanese ..'
The US has proposed a negotiating framework which divides the disputes into
five baskets: government procurement, regulatory reform, motor vehicle and
vehicle parts, compliance with existing agreements and economic integration.
Various solutions - some without numerical indicators - will be sought.
Negotiators are expected to move quickly, with a comprehensive framework
scheduled for completion by the Tokyo economic summit next month.
The US approach arises out of the conviction that the structural impediment
initiative, negotiated by the Bush administration with no measures for
progress, was a failure. The new 'holistic' approach is designed 'to
intersect structural and sector problems,' Mr Kantor said.
A July 1 deadline for Japan to open its government procurement market on
construction is likely to pass without sanctions, although, after years of
negotiations and four pacts, less then 1 per cent of Japanese central
government procurement has been going to foreign suppliers.
The criteria could be the number of procurement opportunities open to
foreign suppliers, the transparency of the process, or the foreign market
share.
'We're flexible in dealing with these, but we are not flexible in looking
for results in terms of measurable success,' Mr Kantor said.
The US specifically will push Japan to increase its imports of manufactured
goods. Even a one-third increase would bring Japanese imports up to only
half the level of most industrialised countries.
It is not the US approach that is managed trade but Japan's, according to Mr
Kantor.
'I would say classic managed trade would be not opening your markets and
protecting your industries, while you export critical high-value products to
other countries.'
</TEXT>
