<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / World Trade News: Clinton embarks on broad review of US
trade laws - Anti-Bribery Act Under Scrutiny
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Clinton administration has embarked on a broad review of US trade laws
and practices to root out internal obstacles to American exports.
'We are looking at A-Z,' said Mr Kenneth Brody, chairman of the
Export-Import Bank and co-chairman of the inter-agency Trade Promotion
Co-ordinating Committee, which is conducting the review. Among laws under
scrutiny are the US export control regime and the foreign corrupt practices
act, which forbids US companies from bribing local officials.
The US export licensing system and the anti-bribery law have long been seen
by American business as burdens not borne by their foreign competitors.
Export controls are time-consuming, expensive and uncertain. The
anti-bribery law is considered vague and ambiguous and troublesome to small
companies which cannot afford high legal fees.
'If bribery is acceptable form in another country and every other country in
the world accepts that and we don't, what does that mean for our exports?'
Mr Brody said.
Business lobbyists say it is a particularly critical issue for operations in
the former Soviet Union, where US investment is being encouraged but, by
most accounts, it is impossible to operate without bribery.
The administration is working closely with its business sector to examine
these obstacles and to co-ordinate the more than 150 export promotion
programmes spread over 19 agencies in the US government.
In part, this new pragmatism is a recognition by the administration that
this is no longer a world of two superpowers but one in which 'our economic
strength will determine our diplomatic and foreign strength,' Mr Brody said.
It is also an indication that the US may do more than pay lip-service to the
ideal of an open trading system. Many trade experts see exports as the best
medicine available for the manufacturing sector, which needs to supply
overseas as well as domestic markets if it is to achieve the highest levels
of efficiency.
The Trade Promotion Co-ordinating Committee, which is headed by Mr Ron
Brown, the commerce secretary, was created by Congress last year to produce
by next September a strategy to promote US exports and a unified budget
consistent with trade priorities.
One of its early targets may well be the US budget for promotion of farm
exports. The General Accounting Office last year released a study finding
that Dollars 2bn, or 74 per cent of total US outlays for trade promotion,
went to support agriculture, which comprises only 10 per cent of US exports.
The political might of the congressional agriculture committees accounts for
the distortion, and it is not clear the administration can alter it.
</TEXT>
<XX>
