<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Open season on energy tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SENATORS and lobbyists yesterday jostled to push their preferred form of
energy tax after the Clinton administration admitted that its plans to levy
a tax on the thermal content of fuels was dead.
Suggestions ranged from a transport fuel levy, to a general energy tax based
on value, to a far-reaching consumption or value-added tax.
Mr Lloyd Bentsen, treasury secretary, said the tax details would be worked
out with the Senate finance committee. 'I'm confident it will not be based
on the British thermal unit,' he said, as the administration had originally
proposed.
Mr Bentsen, who as former senator for Texas is no stranger to the ways of
the petroleum industry, sharply criticised the big oil companies for a
lobbying campaign that turned senators from energy states against the BTU
tax.
'Special interests did quite a job. . . They had some hired guns that
frankly presented some quite distorted figures,' he said in a television
interview yesterday.
One leading participant in the energy tax debate is Senator John Breaux from
the oil-producing state of Louisiana, who yesterday suggested a 7 cents a
gallon levy on all transport fuels.
The administration has been reluctant to adopt a tax focus-ed purely on
transport because of its uneven impact on plains and western states where
much longer distances often have to be driven than in the more densely
populated east.
