<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Riordan LA win setback for Clinton
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR RICHARD RIORDAN, a white conservative Republican lawyer and financier,
has been elected mayor of Los Angeles, in an upset for the Democratic party
and a setback for President Bill Clinton, who had endorsed his opponent, Mr
Michael Woo, a Chinese American liberal Democrat.
Mr Riordan's election reflects a high voting turnout among the affluent
suburban and predominantly white segments of the electorate, where he has
drawn strong support. Although only 40 per cent of Los Angeles voters are
white, they typically make up two-thirds of those who cast their ballots.
However, his victory signals a deepening chasm between racial and
economically disparate groups in the second largest US city, sections of
which were devastated by last year's riots.
'Fear and despair must come to an end. We must create a will in every
Angeleno to turn this city around,' Mr Riordan declared at a victory rally
on Tuesday night. However, critics give him low marks as a consensus-builder
and question his ability to unite the city's diverse population.
Mr Riordan, 63, will succeed Tom Bradley, a Democrat and one of the first
black mayors of a large US city, who is retiring after 20 years in office.
Mr Riordan spent Dollars 3m of his own money and raised an additional
Dollars 3m to sell himself to Los Angeles voters as a political outsider who
is 'tough enough to turn LA around.' Citing his business accomplishments,
including the turnaround of Mattel, a toy manufacturer that faced insolvency
in the mid-1980s, Mr Riordan succeeded in persuading voters that he could
bring new jobs to the city at a time when local industry is being hit by
cutbacks in defence spending.
During the election campaign, Mr Riordan tried to distance himself from such
former business associates as Michael Milken, the junk bond dealer who was
convicted of securities fraud. 'My involvement with Mike Milken has been in
a charitable context,' said Mr Riordan, who serves on the board of the
Milken family Foundation.
The centrepiece of Mr Riordan's election campaign has been a plan to lease
the LA International airport to private industry and to use the income to
hire 3,000 additional police officers. He reasoned that if people feel safer
in LA, businesses are more likely to be attracted to the city.
Opponents of Mr Riordan question the viability of the airport deal. They
also charge that Mr Riordan represents a throwback to the days when
political power in LA was held by an elite of predominantly white
businessmen. One of the biggest challenges facing Mr Riordan when he takes
office on July 1, will be to win over the city council, which is dominated
by Democratic liberals and holds veto power over some of the city's most
important commissions, including those that run the airport and water and
power departments.
Mr Riordan, a Princeton philosophy graduate and a University of Michigan
graduate in law, moved to Los Angeles in 1956 to work for a law firm. He is
a land developer and investment banker. Mr Riordan has long exerted his
influence in LA politics through large campaign contributions and service on
various commissions.
</TEXT>
