<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / US urges EC to curb high-tech sales to Iran
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LUXEMBOURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US yesterday pressed the European Community to curb sales of high
technology to Iran on the grounds that the Tehran regime is seeking to
develop nuclear, biological and chemical weapons.
Mr Warren Christopher, US secretary of state, launched the initiative during
a meeting with EC foreign ministers in Luxembourg in which he implicitly
criticised European companies for selling 'dual use' technology to Iran -
items with both civilian and military applications.
Mr Christopher noted pointedly that the US had curbed its sales in this area
'at considerable cost' to its export industries. He urged the Europeans to
support the idea that Iran should not enjoy normal commercial relations.
After the meeting, both sides agreed to launch a joint EC-US study on Iran's
effort to acquire weapons of mass destruction and the problem of nuclear
non-proliferation.
This will include sharing of intelligence, and is intended to be part of a
collective western effort to prevent more countries joining the nuclear
club.
Mr Christopher painted Iran as the lead villain in its efforts to acquire
weapons of mass destruction. He called non-proliferation 'the most important
issue of the 1990s.'
In the past 12 months, the US has become increasingly concerned about Iran's
effort to develop nuclear and chemical weapons technology. But it has tended
to direct its warnings more at China and Russia rather than the EC.
In the 1980s, both US and European companies sold dual-use technology to
Iraq to bolster President Saddam Hussein during his war with Iran. The sales
were carried out with the approval of western governments, including the
Bush administration, because of the fear of the spread of Islamic
fundamentalism into the Middle East.
The US focus on Iran appeared to take aback some EC member states. Though
all of the Twelve agree with the need to step up non-proliferation efforts,
the consensus is that other countries such as Syria and Iraq also need to be
put on the watch-list.
</TEXT>
