<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Chinese leadership drifts and divides: Overheating economy
hinders easy transition to life-after-Deng
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY WALKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JUST TWO months after China's media hailed a showcase parliamentary session
designed partly to bolster collective leadership, the best-laid plans for a
smooth transition to a post-Deng Xiaoping era appear shaky.
The continued absence from public view of Mr Li Peng, the ailing premier,
intensifying concerns over Mr Deng's own health, worries over economic
overheating, clear signs of factional manoeuvring within the leadership and
a hesitant performance by the ruling Communist party, are all factors
contributing to an impression of drift.
'I feel that things are quite unstable, almost like 1988. Things seems to be
running away, lacking direction. The overwhelming impression is one of
drift,' said a western official who monitors internal developments.
While China's economy continues to rocket ahead, the political ground
appears to be shifting and leadership foundations that Mr Deng had put in
place seem more insecure; not that his choices of personnel to carry on his
work ever inspired a great deal of confidence.
Mr Li Peng's illness - he is believed to have suffered a heart attack in the
last week of April - and thus his withdrawal from an active leadership role
has merely served to expose flaws in the collective structure that the
88-year-old Mr Deng had hoped would be an enduring legacy.
Among more revealing developments recently has been the conspicuously more
assertive performance in Mr Li's lingering absence of Mr Jiang Zemin,
China's party boss and recently-appointed state president. Mr Jiang, aged
67, whom Chinese propaganda has been referring to as the 'core' of the new
leadership based on the seven-member politburo standing committee, is being
accorded much more prominence in the government-controlled media. This has
been accompanied by reports of him moving political cronies from his days as
mayor of Shanghai into key positions in the central government, the security
apparatus and the media.
He has also intervened in the economic debate, urging restraint on growth
and an intensification of the campaign against corruption and 'money
worship'. In forthright comments on the economy he was trespassing into an
area not previously in his domain, and which risked bringing him into
conflict with the reformists patronised by Mr Deng.
In a speech delivered on April 1, immediately after the annual session of
the National People's Congress endorsed Dengist 'high growth' policies, Mr
Jiang warned of 'major upheavals' unless the economy was reined in. He
mentioned specifically dangers of inflation and a widening gap between rich
and poor.
His intervention - discussion about an overheating economy has been raging
for months in the Chinese leadership - was not revealed until it was
published in late May in a Chinese-funded Hong Kong magazine. His remarks
were then given prominence in the mainland press, but, what is intriguing,
the People's Daily put its report of Mr Jiang's speech beside an editorial
calling for faster reform of the 'socialist market economy'.
Such juxtaposition of apparently contradictory views on the central issue
facing China tended to give credence to talk of divisions in the leadership,
with the economy providing the battleground for a broader contest.
In this uncertain period the military is assuming more than usual
importance, and already there are signs that leadership contenders are
courting key military personnel.
Amid fears that the economic boom will bring about a political loosening,
and thus an erosion of party control, political campaigns aimed at
'strengthening ideology', such as the present appeals to altruism, appear
forlorn.
'I think they're very confused,' a western official said of party
propagandists. 'It's almost as if they're trying to remind themselves of
what communism is. They really have no new ideas. People don't want to hear
about struggling hard. That's what they've done all their lives.'
</TEXT>
