<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Brittan admits flaws in aid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Community is to reform its Ecu1.5bn (Pounds 1.18bn) aid
programmes in the former Soviet bloc, following allegations that they are
slow and poorly managed.
Sir Leon Brittan, EC commissioner for external economic affairs, yesterday
promised to streamline and decentralise the Ecu1bn Phare programme - aimed
at central and eastern Europe - and the Ecu500m Tacis programme for the
former Soviet Union.
Addressing the European Parliament's external relations and budgetary
control committees, Sir Leon said the Community needed 'to learn from its
mistakes as well as its successes'.
MEPs attacked the Commission, manager of the Phare and Tacis programmes, for
the slow disbursement of funds, which are used for technical assistance and
advice in areas such as food distribution, privatisation, banking and civil
service reform. The deputies also took up the criticisms of some east
European beneficiaries that the programmes rely heavily on costly
consultants, favouring northern EC member states which are strong in that
sector.
Sir Leon conceded that bureaucratic procedures and a lack of specialist
know-how had hampered the work of the EC in eastern Europe. 'We are
increasingly discovering that the pool of qualified know-how is limited and
sometimes less qualified than we and the beneficiaries expect,' he said.
He also promised to take tough action to prevent member states from
influencing the selection of projects in favour of their own commercial
interests.
'Phare and Tacis are not a form of outdoor relief for member state
consultants,' Sir Leon said, adding that the Commission would try to ensure
that projects were selected 'purely on objective criteria' in future.
Sir Leon said the main elements of reform would include greater involvement
of beneficiary countries in helping to make the projects work, with the EC
restricting itself to development of the framework policy.
'Such a change would lead to less bureaucracy, more flexibility and a
greater appreciation of the Community's efforts by the recipient countries,'
he said.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>RUZ  Russia, East Europe.
    XLZ  East Europe.
