<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Italian MPs to curb 'suspect' secret service
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Italian parliament is to seek broader powers to monitor more closely the
activities of the country's intelligence services.
The tighter controls were promised yesterday by Mr Ugo Pecchioli, a senator
for the Party of the Democratic Left and newly elected head of the
parliamentary intelligence committee. The move follows the shake-up last
Friday by Mr Carlo Azeglio Ciampi, the prime minister, of the senior ranks
of the intelligence services.
The government and parliament are anxious to bring the intelligence services
under strict scrutiny following suspicions that some of their members or
ex-members may have had a hand in recent bombings in Rome and Florence,
formally attributed to the mafia. The authorities suspect a repeat of the
1970s when it is thought that the mafia, right wing organisations and the
secret services sought to create tension in order to swing public opinion
away from the left.
The intelligence services are divided into the SISMI and SISDE. The SISMI is
responsible for intelligence gathering and operations to protect national
security and carries out most of the services' foreign activities. The SISDE
is concerned with domestic intelligence.
Under legislation approved in 1977 when the services were first reorganised,
parliament can only be informed of their activities by the prime minister.
However, Mr Ciampi discovered after the May 27 car bomb at the Uffizi
Gallery in Florence that the intelligence services are not obliged to inform
fully the prime minister of their activities.
This, coupled with the suspicion that the two services harboured agents
linked to the mafia and extreme-right wing groupings, led to last week's
personnel changes. New deputy directors were appointed for both services and
new heads were appointed to three of SISDE's four operational divisions.
Yesterday Mr Pecchioli, who fought with the partisans during the second
world war, said it was vital to establish 'if there had been people acting
outside orders or if there have been lapses of inefficiency' in the recent
car bombings. He said parliament's control was far too limited, especially
now that the cold war had ended. He said insufficient effort had been made
to clean out an intelligence community compromised by links with the secret
masonic lodge P2.
</TEXT>
