<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Japan carworkers top of earnings league in world motor
industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN, the world's biggest car producer, had the highest gross hourly wage
rates in the world automobile industry last year, according to a study by
the German motor industry federation (VDA). Japanese car assembly line
workers also worked the highest number of hours.
Germany and Sweden had the highest total motor industry wage costs, however,
because of a much heavier burden of social costs such as payroll tax or
national insurance. Carworkers in Germany and Sweden, along with Italy, also
worked the fewest hours.
Britain had the lowest total wage costs (gross wages plus social costs such
as payroll tax) in the developed world's motor industry last year, a
position it has held for six of the past seven years.
At the same time UK carworkers worked longer hours than anywhere else in
Europe, and Britain had one of the lowest levels of corporate taxation.
The German motor industry, which is facing severe problems as new vehicle
sales plummet, has suffered a sharp decline in its competitiveness,
according to the VDA figures. Total industry wage costs at DM47 (Pounds 19)
an hour were the highest in the world last year based on average exchange
rates.
The position deteriorated further in the wake of last autumn's turmoil in
European currency markets. Based on exchange rates in December 1992 German
vehicle makers had total wage costs two-thirds higher than the average of
DM28.3 in the rest of Europe, and 37 per cent higher than in both the US and
Japan at DM34.4 per hour.
Adding to the German industry's problems its carworkers enjoyed some of the
shortest working hours at 1,483 hours per year in 1991 (the latest VDA
figures available), a third less than the 2,181 hours worked on average by
their Japanese counterparts and 27 per cent less than the 2,022 hours worked
annually in the US.
According to the VDA figures, German carworkers worked 350 hours a year less
than their equivalents in the UK (1,830 hours a year) and more than 100
hours a year less than in France (1,608) and Spain (1,654).
Carworkers in Sweden and Italy had the shortest annual working hours at
1,388 and 1,409 respectively.
The VDA claims that German motor industry competitiveness is further
burdened by one of the highest levels of corporate taxation, with a tax rate
of around 66 per cent compared with 52 per cent in France and only 33 per
cent in the UK.
</TEXT>
