<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Milosevic pressed over UN sanctions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE international mediators on Bosnia, Lord Owen and Mr Thorvald
Stoltenberg, flew to Belgrade yesterday in an attempt to persuade Serbia's
president, Mr Slobodan Milosevic, to lift his objections to posting UN
monitors along Serbia's border with Bosnia.
Serbia claims its authorities are enforcing sanctions against Bosnia
following the Bosnian Serbs' rejection last month of the Vance/Owen peace
plan. However, fuel and other supplies are continuing to cross the border.
As UN sanctions bite more deeply Mr Milosevic may be more willing to have
international monitors posted along the Serbian side of the river Drina that
marks the border. The dismissal last week of Mr Dobrica Cosic, the federal
president and an opponent of monitors, removes an important obstacle to the
proposal.
Lord Owen also stressed that the Vance-Owen plan remained 'the framework for
a settlement,' adding that the creation of six safe areas for Moslems was
only a 'short-term solution, to stop Bosnian Serb attacks on areas that are
clearly and unequivocally Moslem or Croat'. However, his admission that he
had failed to convince Bosnian Serb leaders to allow UN observers and relief
convoys into Gorazde, one of three UN-designated safe areas in eastern
Bosnia, underlines the problems involved in trying to set up safe areas
without a ceasefire in effect.
Gorazde, an industrial town close to the border with Serbia, has come under
heavy artillery attack by Bosnian Serb forces in the past two weeks. Its
population doubled to 70,000 with the arrival of Moslems from surrounding
villages. Earlier this week, the town's last supply route was cut as Serb
forces closed in.
'It's clear the Bosnian Serbs intend to consolidate their territorial gains
by squeezing the safe areas in eastern Bosnia out of existence,' a western
diplomat said.
Serbian commanders have prevented UN relief convoys from reaching Srebenica,
another safe area in eastern Bosnia, where 300 UN troops are responsible for
protecting more than 20,000 Moslems.
Bosnian radio reported that Ukrainian soldiers serving in the UN protection
force yesterday fired on unidentified armed groups trying to reach Zepa, the
third safe area, a small town in a mountain ravine where 16,000 Moslems have
sought refuge.
The future of the other three safe areas may be decided by the outcome of a
new Moslem offensive against Croatians in central Bosnia, aimed at
tightening control over areas with a mainly Moslem population. Moslem forces
this week captured Travnik, strategically placed between two
Moslem-controlled strongholds, also burning surrounding villages.
After Sarajevo, the largest safe area would be Tuzla, an industrial centre
with 340,000 residents, where there has been little fighting. One reason is
that both Serbs and Moslems fear provoking massive destruction if a chemical
factory in the city was shelled.
The Bihac district, a mainly agricultural area with 200,000 residents, has
also remained relatively quiet with UN convoys facing few problems in
getting through.
</TEXT>
