<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Yeltsin heads for new clash with rival
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Boris Yeltsin yesterday invited parliamentary deputies to join his
constitutional convention in an attempt to give it more legitimacy and head
off opposition from Mr Ruslan Khasbulatov, the parliamentary speaker.
The deputies agreed to send Mr Khasbulatov, who is waging an increasingly
desperate campaign to make parliament the centre of Russian political power,
to the convention. But they set tough conditions for his participation,
including a retraction by Mr Yeltsin of his statement that the old system of
soviets (Bolshevik mini-parliaments at local level) was incompatible with
democracy.
The stage is now set for yet another confrontation between the two men. The
rules of Russia's political jungle - which lacks a strong party structure or
any sense of personal responsibility - mean individuals tend to follow
whoever is stronger at any given moment. Hence the desertion of Mr
Khasbulatov following Mr Yeltsin's referendum victory by some of his top
lieutenants in parliament's praesidium.
Leading this rebellion is Mr Nikolai Ryabov, a hardline Communist, who only
recently, when the president appeared to be on the ropes, jeered at both Mr
Yeltsin and his market reform plans.
Mr Khasbulatov, however, shows no sign of abandoning his campaign even
though his support is shrinking. His strategy centres on delaying as long as
possible the convening of a Congress of People's Deputies, or full
parliament, which he commands, to consider a new constitution. This will
allow time for the country's economic troubles to worsen further and for Mr
Yeltsin's referendum victory last month to be be forgotten. For the same
reason, Mr Yeltsin wants to push through a new constitution as quickly as
possible.
In addition, both men are appealing to Russia's constitutent regions and
republics for support. But in so doing they are only encouraging the
country's disintegration by weaking the credibility of the federal
institutions in Moscow.
When all the constitutional complexities are set aside, the only really
intractable issue is how powers should be divided between a previously
bloated parliament and an over-weak executive. In an apocalyptic speech to
parliament yesterday, Mr Khasbulatov warned of the dangers of bypassing the
Congress in enacting a new constitution, accused the president of wanting to
set up a dictatorship, and said a corrupt administration was destroying the
economy.
He has everything to lose from a dissolution of the Congress of People's
Deputies if a new constitution is ushered in. A native of Chechnya, which
has declared independence from Russia and declared him a persona non grata,
Mr Khasbulatov will not even be able to stand for parliament at the next
election.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>RUZ  Russia, East Europe.
