<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 93 / Bitter Lamont savages Major: Speech plunges premiership deep
into crisis
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SAVAGE attack by Mr Norman Lamont last night plunged Mr John Major's
premiership into its gravest political crisis since he replaced Mrs Margaret
Thatcher in 1990.
The former chancellor, sacked two weeks ago in a cabinet reshuffle, told a
spellbound House of Commons that Mr Major's beleaguered administration acted
as if it was 'in office but not in power'.
Clearly relishing his revenge, Mr Lamont warned that unless it abandoned its
preoccupation with opinion polls and newspaper headlines, 'the government
will not survive and will not deserve to survive'.
Directing his comments at the prime minister's leadership, he said: 'There
is something wrong with the way we make our decisions. The government
listens too much to the pollsters and the party managers . . . There is too
much short-termism, too much reacting to events, not enough shaping of
events.'
His speech lacked the devastating political force of those delivered by the
then Mr Nigel Lawson and Sir Geoffrey Howe in the final stages of the
Thatcher era.
After the crises of the past few months, ministers and Conservative MPs were
left wondering nonetheless whether Mr Major's premiership would now survive
the rest of the year.
But there is no obvious challenger to the prime minister. His close friends
were also taking comfort last night from signs of a backlash against Mr
Lamont for what one minister described as the former chancellor's
'self-serving disloyalty'.
With the prime minister sitting, white-faced, in the Commons chamber, Mr
Lamont said he had tried vainly for two-and-a-half years to persuade him to
give independence to the Bank of England.
As the bitterness seeped slowly through his 20-minute resignation speech, Mr
Lamont also accused the prime minister of undermining the credibility of
economic policy by allowing bad political news to dictate the timing of
interest rate cuts. Friends said later he had been referring to the 1
percentage point cut in rates to 6 per cent at the start of this year.
Exposing the struggle which led eventually to his dismissal, Mr Lamont
claimed that, after the humiliation of sterling's withdrawal from the
European exchange rate mechanism last September, Mr Major had told him not
to resign.
By implication he also blamed Sir Norman Fowler, the Conservative party
chairman, and Mr Richard Ryder, the chief whip, for forcing Mr Major to sack
him.
Mr Lamont's attack - the latest in a series of blows to Mr Major's political
authority - overshadowed a concerted attempt by the prime minister and by Mr
Kenneth Clarke, the new chancellor, to relaunch the government's economic
strategy.
Mr Major told MPs that he saw little prospect of sterling's return to the
ERM during this parliament, while Mr Clarke emphasised in a series of
interviews and speeches that his priority was to sustain the economic
recovery.
Mr Lamont's speech also provided a perfect platform for Mr John Smith, the
Labour leader, to launch a scathing personal attack on the prime minister's
leadership.
While Mr Smith ridiculed the government's economic management, Mr Paddy
Ashdown, the Liberal Democrat leader, predicted that Mr Lamont's on-slaught
marked the beginning of the end of Mr Major's leadership.
The prime minister struggled to play down the significance of the attack -
suggesting, for example, that he would have supported the idea of an
independent central bank if ways could have been found to preserve
democratic accountability.
Mr Major was driven to respond to Mr Lamont's uncompromising defence of his
record in the Treasury with the sharp retort: 'A strong government needs
political skills as well when leading a democratic society and, in
particular, handling a lively House of Commons with a small majority.'
Mr Clarke strongly defended the prime minister and dismissed suggestions
that he was poised to replace him. He said he did not recognise the former
chancellor's description of the way the government operated.
But the grim faces on the Tory benches and the lack of conviction with which
many called on colleagues to rally round the prime minister suggested that
Mr Lamont's charges had struck a dangerous chord. Mr Lamont's accusation
that Mr Major prefers to react to events rather than shape them mirrored
recent grumbling among Tory MPs. Some senior figures warned that unless Mr
Major re-established his grip on the government by autumn there would be
strong pressure for him to stand down.
During a speech in which he absolved himself of any blame for the economic
problems of the past few years, Mr Lamont dwelt on the events which had led
to last September's ERM debacle.
He said that at one point he had suggested sterling's suspension from the
system, although he admitted that this would not have been in time to
prevent Black Wednesday. Suggesting that he had then been ready to resign, a
view rejected immediately by the prime minister's office, Mr Lamont said he
had remained as chancellor because of loyalty to the prime minister.
Parliament, Page 7
Joe Rogaly, Page 18
Editorial Comment, Page 19
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
