<PROFILE>_AN-DFICHAEDFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930609
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 93 / UK Company News: New brands help Seton Healthcare to Pounds
6m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SETON Healthcare, the medical products and sports equipment group which has
expanded rapidly since coming to the market two years ago, has turned in a
strong growth in profits.
Under FRS 3, restated pre-tax profits for the year to February 28 increased
from Pounds 2.84m to Pounds 6.1m, but last year's figure was depressed by an
exceptional charge of Pounds 1.49m. Adjusting for the exceptional losses,
profits growth was 41 per cent.
Turnover rose by 4 per cent, from Pounds 37.2m to Pounds 38.6m. The group
said operating profit as a percentage of sales had increased from 13.7 to
17.1 per cent and a further improvement was predicted.
Seton's acquisition focus has been on over-the-counter brands, which now
account for more than 25 per cent of sales. Four acquisitions - Mycota,
Betadine, Cupal and some brands from Crookes - were completed during the
year at a cost ofPounds 14.2m.
The healthcare division's sales increased by 6 per cent to Pounds 33.6m.
Taking account of acquisitions and disposals, its underlying organic growth
rate was 8 per cent, and operating profits rose from Pounds 4.54m to Pounds
5.98m. The group said the brands acquired had helped it to become one of the
top 10 companies in terms of OTC sales to UK pharmacies.
The sports and leisure division's sales dipped from Pounds 5.56m to Pounds
5m, but its operating profits were 7 per cent higher at Pounds 605,000,
which Mr Iain Cater, Seton's chief executive, described as an outstanding
performance.
Adjusting for the exceptionals, earnings per share rose by 28 per cent to
16.3p (12.7p). A final dividend of 4.1p (3.6p) gives a total for the year of
5.8p (5.1p).
COMMENT
These results maintain Seton's impressive track record. The increased
profitability partly reflects the group's move towards higher-margin OTC
products, but also shows the benefits of increased economies of scale in
manufacture and distribution. The sports business - selling shin guards and
goalkeeper's gloves - is also well placed for any recovery in spending.
However, the group now has quite a lot to digest, and will invest Pounds
4m-Pounds 5m in a new facility in Oldham over the next two years. Forecast
earnings of Pounds 8.1m put the shares on a prospective multiple of 19.5.
That looks up with events, particularly since the company will not hesitate
to come to the market to fund further acquisitions.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Seton Healthcare Group.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2834 Pharmaceutical Preparations.
    P3949 Sporting and Athletic Goods, NEC.
</IN>
