<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 93 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE derivatives sector opened well in London as US buyers chased the June
futures contract on the FT-SE 100 Index. The contract quickly advanced to
the 2,850 area, but then ran into a stone wall as the buyers faded away and
a handful of nervous sellers chipped away at the earlier levels.
US buying appeared to be no more than position closing in London by two US
investment houses seeking to cover overnight losses in New York. For the
rest of the session it was the London locals, or independent traders, who
held sway.
There was further switching of holdings from the June contract into the
September paper, which will take over leadership of the market later this
month. Dealers said the differential of around 20 points between the two was
in line with expectations at this stage.
Business in traded options fell to 19,037 contracts from Monday's 26,069,
with the FT-SE 100 option decreasing its contribution sharply to 2,893.
Among individual contracts, British Aerospace, feeding off a strong share
price, topped the actives with 1,762 lots. Dealers see the stock's strong
performance since the end of last year as confirmation of recovery
prospects.
British Airways was close behind with 1,423 lots dealt, and there was
renewed interest in TSB (1,223 contracts), although traders saw no reason
for the renewed bid speculation.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
<XX>
