<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 93 / Price rises help lift Anglian Water by 8%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ANGLIAN Water, one of the biggest privatised water companies, yesterday
announced profits in line with expectations but said its unregulated
businesses lost money due to recession and start- up costs.
Pre-tax profits increased 8.2 per cent from Pounds 171.3m to Pounds 185.4m
in the year to March 31, helped by price increases and a Pounds 3.3m gain on
land sales. Mr Bernard Henderson, chairman, said the results represented a
considerable achievement, especially in Anglian's regulated water and sewage
business.
Turnover increased 11.5 per cent to Pounds 583.2m, with average price
increases at 9.4 per cent. Operating costs grew more quickly, reflecting
expansion of the unregulated businesses. Operating profits increased 9.1 per
cent to Pounds 211.6m.
Unregulated businesses, strengthened in February by the acquisition of the
Swedish-based process engineering company Nordic Water, made an operating
loss of Pounds 4.4m on sales of Pounds 29m. Mr Alan Smith, managing
director, said he hoped the division would make a profit after interest
costs this year.
Anglian has reacted to criticism of its disconnection policy - the number of
customers cut off fell from 1,200 to 236. But bad debt provisions shot up
from Pounds 3.4m to Pounds 8.4m.
Interest costs increased by nearly a third to Pounds 29.5m. Net borrowings
rose by a similar amount to Pounds 392.5m as the capital spending programme
gathered momentum. Gearing increased from 23 per cent to nearly 29 per cent.
Anglian said it had won backing from customers to raise capital spending and
prices beyond the legal minimum in the second half of the decade. Ofwat, the
water regulator, will next year rule on companies' pricing levels. Most are
finding resistance from customers to higher prices.
Earnings per share increased 9.1 per cent to 56.4p. The company recommended
a final dividend of 14.3p to make a total of 21.2p, a 9.3 per cent increase.
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
