<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Dark delusions on the Conservative
right - Political Notebook
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE arrogance is breathtaking. Follow the scenario now being mapped out by
some of Mr John Major's so-called supporters on the Tory back benches at
Westminster.
The prime minister, already badly wounded, is delivered a fatal blow by a
Conservative defeat in the Christchurch by-election. He struggles on until
the autumn.
A stormy party conference (spiced with the revelations promised in Lady
Thatcher's memoirs) and an anaemic economic recovery sap what remains of his
political authority. The men in grey suits appear on the steps of 10 Downing
Street.
Mr Major decides not to wait for a formal leadership challenge and retires
on health grounds to Huntingdon. Mr Norman Lamont considers justice has been
done. The Tory party elects by acclamation Mr Kenneth Clarke as prime
minister.
There are one or two conditions, of course. The right wing of the party, so
disenchanted now with the leader they chose to replace Lady Thatcher, demand
that the centrist Mr Clarke don a suitably ideo-logical straitjacket.
Mr Michael Portillo must be given the chancellorship - with a free hand to
dismantle the welfare state. Mr John Redwood is promoted from Wales to
health. Mr Peter Lilley keeps command of social security.
Mr Michael Spicer, the self-proclaimed leader of the Fresh Start group of
anti-Maastricht MPs, returns to the government as minister for Europe.
All that agreed, the Euro-sceptic right is perfectly happy to sustain the
government in office for another two or three years.
The fantasy does not end there. For all the valiant efforts of Mr John
Edmonds to ensure that Labour never again becomes a party of government, Mr
John Smith wins the general election.
Mr Clarke goes the way of his two predecessors. He is replaced, yes, by Mr
Portillo. The true heir to Thatcherism has four years in opposition to
stiffen the ideological backbone that sustained the Conservatives in the
1980s.
If, by some mishap, Mr Clarke wins the election, then Mr Portillo, still a
stripling of 43, remains well placed to assume the mantle four or five years
later.
No wonder Mr Major is weary.
For the above represents not the dark delusion of one of Westminster's
occasional, overlooked eccentrics. Instead, give or take a detail of two, it
encapsulates the embittered dream of two dozen MPs on the Tory back benches.
Add one or two further modifications and up to 50 - including a handful of
ministers - might sign up.
So deep during the past year has their hatred of Maastricht run, so great is
their detachment from the world of government, that Mr Major's very own
Militant Tendency now operates outside the para-meters of political logic.
That brings us to the arrogance. There is no mention of the electorate -
save as a convenient instrument for Mr Clarke's early replacement by Mr
Portillo. In this self-obsessed world, politics is no longer about such
esoteric notions as good government but about revenge and ideological
purity.
There is no reference to the commitments offered to the voters barely 15
months ago. Instead, a new dictum is applied: Conservative manifesto pledges
operate not for the lifetime of a parliament, but only during that of the
leader who penned them.
Of course, it will not happen like that. Politics is not susceptible to neat
blueprints. The notion that a few dozen backbench MPs can choose now who
might lead the Tories in five or 10 years' time - assuming there is still a
party to lead - lies outside the realm of sensible politics.
So, too, does idea that the party can swap its prime minister every two or
three years and remain a coherent force in politics. Mr Portillo is an
astute politician. He might one day lead his party. But he must tremble at
the thought of the future mapped out by Mr Major's enemies.
For all their noise, the Tory right remains a minority. Taken as a whole it
can claim, at most, the support of a third of the 332-strong parliamentary
party. That is a distinctly generous estimate. The hard-line Eurosceptics
represent half again of that number.
So Mr Major can relax?
Well, no. If his fortunes continue to slide, the ideologues may enlist the
support of that other lethal grouping in the Tory party - the pathological
panickers. They are scornful of their colleagues' bizarre plan for the
rebirth of Thatcherism. Yet some are already whispering that salvation in
the end may lie with Mr Clarke.
The odds still are all this will turn out of be a particularly acute attack
of midsummer madness. But it is no longer possible to be sure. In its
present state, the Conservative party is capable of anything - including
setting off on the route to self-destruction.
</TEXT>
